<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Defense Projects Face Costly Delays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Substantial cost increases and
further delays in completing key defense projects ranging from the
Challenger 2 tank to the Eurofighter are disclosed in a report
presented to the British parliament today.
</P>
<P>
The cost of completing 23 of the most important programs has
risen by more than 2.19 billion US dollars or almost 9 percent. On
22 of the projects average delays have increased by five months to
40 months.
</P>
<P>
In its annual report on the procurement projects, the National
Audit Office (NAO) revealed that cost over-runs and delays were
getting worse, despite repeated assurances from the Ministry of
Defense that it was taking a tighter grip on the program.
</P>
<P>
The NAO also revealed that procurement was so badly behind
schedule that Britain's defenses were being put at risk, and that
outdated ships, tanks and aircraft were being patched up at a cost
of 640 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that delays in replacing the assault ships
Fearless and Intrepid have left the Royal Navy facing difficulties
in launching an amphibious assault.
</P>
<P>
Six projects have been pushed back by 12 months or more in the
past year alone while in seven cases delays are now stretching to
five years.
</P>
<P>
The NAO complained that the Ministry of Defense failed to build
sufficient guarantees on reliability into the original contract.
"There are clear lessons to be learned from Challenger 2 on
contracting for reliability in other projects," it said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Ministry of Defense said, "There is room for
improvement and the secretary of state is committed to
improvement." "We are doing so in some areas already -- we want to
build on best practice," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
