<HEADLINE> Israeli Arab Delegation Returns From Controversial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A 42-member Israeli Arab
delegation returned home today from a controversial visit to
Syria, saying that Damascus still wants to make peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which also included several lawmakers from the
opposition Labor and Meretz parties, paid a week-long visit to
Syria, during which they held talks with Syrian President Hafez
Assad and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon their return at the Ben-Gurion
Airport, Labor lawmaker Salah Tarif said that Syria is still
interested in making peace with Israel, though it believes the
policies of Israeli government are not conducive to concluding
peace.
</P>
<P>
Tarif denied criticism by some parliamentary members that he
presented a letter from Labor leader Ehud Barak to Assad.
</P>
<P>
Assad reportedly said that he could talk peace with Barak, if
the talks would be continued from the point where they broke off
last year under Israel's previous Labor government.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Syrian peace negotiations have been frozen since March
last year following a wave of suicide bombing attacks launched by
Islamic extremists against Israel, and tension between the two
countries has been brewing after the hardline Likud government
came to power in Israel in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Israel has repeatedly called for unconditional resumption of
the peace talks, while Syria insists that the negotiations should
restart from the point where they broke off: Israel's promise to
total withdrawal from the occupied Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
When receiving the Israeli delegation on Tuesday, Assad said
he is still committed to peace but keeping all options open at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
He accused Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of being
an "enemy of peace," stressing that the talks should be
reconvened from where they broke off under the Labor government.
</P>
<P>
The high-profile visit by the Israeli Arab delegation to Syria
caused a political uproar inside Israel. Lawmakers from the
rightist coalition strongly denounced the opposition members of
the delegation for acting like "traitors" by calling a return of
Palestinian refugees in Syria.
</P>
<P>
They also attacked Barak for sending a message to Assad in
which Barak called for the resumption of direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Uzi Landau, Chairman of Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs
and Defense Committee, said Barak was not acting like a political
leader with national duty and making a mistake by sending the
message to Assad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
