<HEADLINE> Canadian Military to Purchase New Copters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Defense Minister Arthur
Eggleton will announce the winner of the bid to supply 16
search-and-rescue helicopters next month, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
The minister also hopes to proceed quickly with the purchase of
ship-based helicopters, Canada's leading newspaper the Globe and
Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
"I expect to be able to make a decision in September," Eggleton
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some bidders are hoping that the 430 million U.S. dollars'
search-and rescue deal will lead to the 1 billion dollars'
contract to supply the Navy with 35 maritime helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Eggleton said he wants to move quickly to replace the
accident-prone, ship-borne Sea Kings helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Though the Canadian government has promised to replace the
copters, the cabinet has not yet approved the spending, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think the (maritime purchase) is too far away,"
Eggleton noted.
</P>
<P>
After its election victory in 1993, the Liberal government led
by Jean Chretien canceled a 3.5 billion-dollar contract for 48
EH-101 helicopters, which were to serve both the search-and-rescue
operation and the ship-borne maritime defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
