<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- Israel eased slightly the blockade it set up two weeks ago
around the West Bank cities of Hebron and Ramallah, allowing
Palestinians living in those areas to leave for the first time
since a suicide bombing in Jerusalem. But Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat said the measures were inadequate and gave a speech in
Ramallah saying Israel's continued refusal to let Palestinian
workers into the country indicated that its government was not
prepared to pursue the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. government said it would end cash disability
benefits for at least 95,180 children, mostly suffering from
mental disorders, representing more than half of all those whose
cases have been reviewed under strict new standards established by
the 1996 welfare law, Federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Two cosmonauts returned safely to Earth Thursday, ending a
troubled six-month voyage aboard the Mir space station, whose
frequent breakdowns threaten to cripple Russia's space program.
</P>
<P>
-- Footprints left on the sandy shore of a South African
lagoon after a violent rainstorm some 117,000 years ago, and
amazingly preserved, have been identified as the oldest fossilized
tracks of an anatomically modern human ever found.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- UPS and Teamsters resumed contract talks, and continued what
they called a "substantive and detailed" meeting into the night.
Neither side was willing to predict when the union's 12-day-old
strike might end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
