<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Ex-Fighters Picket Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's war veterans
protesting delays in releasing compensation funds, today picketed
offices of President Robert Mugabe, demanding to see him.
</P>
<P>
The war veterans sang revolutionary songs, danced and
disrupted the free-flow of traffic in the busy Samora Machel
Avenue just outside the main gate to the president's Munhumutapa
offices.
</P>
<P>
They then marched towards Compensation House just a street
away, which houses the office of Minister of Public Service,
Labour and Social Welfare Florence Chitauro, who froze the war
victims compensation cheques in March, this year after
discovering that the funds had been looted.
</P>
<P>
The ex-combatants staged demonstrations in the past few weeks
which often turned violent. Today They wanted to secure an
audience with Mugabe who is patron of the Zimbabwe National
Liberation War Veterans Association.
</P>
<P>
''We are now going to have a fully-fledged demonstration. What
we want is to be given our money and that is all,'' said the war
veterans spokesman Mike Moyo.
</P>
<P>
The ex-combatants had spent most of the morning and part of
the afternoon outside the Ruling Zimbabwe African National Union
(PF) Harare provincial headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The war veterans began to converge on these offices on Thursday.
They vowed not to return to their homes until they had either been
addressed by Mugabe, or they had been given their cheques.
</P>
<P>
The money is to compensate them for injuries sustained in the
war that ushered in Zimbabwe's independence from British colonial
rule in 1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
