<HEADLINE> 4 Hong Kong Residents Drown, 3 Missing in Philippine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Four Hong Kong residents
drowned and three were missing in a sightseeing boat accident on
Manila Bay today, according to the Commissioner's Office of the
Chinese Foreign Ministry in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Chinese Embassy in the Philippines to the
Office said that a group of 45 HK tourists arrived at Manila this
morning and they went sightseeing on Manila Bay at 4:00 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Ten minutes later, the boat, buffeted by strong winds and heavy
waves, capsized at a site not far from the headquarters of the
Philippine Navy, and all the Hong Kong tourists and a local guide
abroad fell into the sea.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine navy immediately dispatched vessels to their
rescue.
A total of 38 HK tourists survived, four (three females, one male)
drowned, and three (two females and one male) were missing. And
the rescue operation was still going on.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Embassy in Manila sent officials to the accident
scene, the hospital and the headquarters of the Philippine Navy.
The Chinese officials conveyed regards to the victims and bought
clothes and food to them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
