<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks to Be Held in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks between the
Burundian government and main Hutu rebels will be held August 25
in the northern Tanzanian town Arusha in a bid to end four years
of civil war in the tiny central African state.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Burundian Minister of External Relations and
Cooperation Luc Rukingama confirmed here today that Burundian
President Pierre Buyoya will meet leaders of the Hutu-led
National Council for the Defense of Democracy (CNDD) there.
</P>
<P>
"The political dialogue remains primarily the responsibility
of Burundi which will go to Arusha in conformity with her
commitments," the minister said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Arusha is the headquarters of the East Africa Cooperation
comprising Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda and also the venue of an
U.N. tribunal on the 1994 genocide in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The expected talks mark that "Burundi enters into an important
stage of the peace process which started a year ago," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Bloodshed conflicts reportedly broke out last month between
the CNDD and the rival Party for the Liberation of the Hutu
People (Palipehutu) which is said furious at the CNDD for
agreeing to attend the talks.
</P>
<P>
Rukingama hailed Kenya's decision earlier this month to lift
its air travel ban on Burundi, urging other countries in the
Great Lakes Region to follow the suit.
</P>
<P>
Burundi experienced "a very hard time" due to the economic
embargo slapped by the Great Lakes countries last year when
Buyoya took power from the civilian government of former
president Sylvester Ntibantunganya in a military coup, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth rate in Burundi is negative now, compared
with around three percent in 1993 when the civil war broke out,
he added.
</P>
<P>
However, following a regional summit on the Burundi conflict
on April 16 in Arusha, sanctions on the country were eased on
food, education, medicine, agricultural inputs and construction
materials.
</P>
<P>
Rukingama arrived here for visit to Kenya earlier this week.
He has held discussioins with senior political and business
leaders of Kenya over bilateral relations and ways to ease the
sanctions on Burundi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
