<DOCNO> XIE19970816.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Watch Out for Revival of Japanese Militarism in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- As people in many Asian countries
marked the 52nd anniversary of Japan's surrender in World War II
today, the evil spirits of Japanese class-A war criminals started
wriggling in the controversial Yasukuni Shrine where the farce of
prayers was being performed.
</P>
<P>
The shrine, which houses the memorial tablets of 14 class-A war
criminals including Japan's wartime prime minister, Hideki Tojo,
and other Japanese military personnel, is a symbol of militarism
in the country.
</P>
<P>
In continuous rain early this morning, a number of Japanese
right-wingers who dream of reviving militarism in the country
started their poor performances at the shrine by distributing
books which called for reversing the historical verdict on Japan's
invasion during World War II.
</P>
<P>
These maniacs termed Japan's invasion of other countries "a
self-defense war," aimed at liberating those Asian countries.
This is a sheer distortion of history.
</P>
<P>
In a hue and cry, they also made a claim that despite the loss,
Japan gained honor from its war against the whole world because it
struck terror into countries like the United States, Britain, the
former Soviet Union, France and China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they tried to seek testimony to deny the fact that
the Japanese invasion troops had forced women from many Asian
countries into sexual slavery.
</P>
<P>
The farce at the shrine went on with an absurd march launched
by a group of elderly men in Imperial Army uniforms, carrying the
former World War II army flag.
</P>
<P>
A 71-year-old veteran, who joined the Japanese Imperial Army in
1942, told reporters that he paid respect to the "martyrs" every
year. There was absolutely no remorse in his words for his wartime
acts.
</P>
<P>
The shrine also saw 11 intellectuals standing erect in the rain
and reading in one voice a statement which called for the
Japanese prime minister to formally visit the Yasukuni shrine.
</P>
<P>
However, Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto had already
formally announced he would not visit the shrine on August 15. Hashimoto
expressed deep remorse for Japan's role in World War II and
expressed deep condolences to war victims at another ceremony held in
Tokyo today.
</P>
<P>
"The last war caused tremendous pain and sorrow not only to our
country but also to people in many countries, particularly those
in neighboring Asian nations," he told the annual gathering.
</P>
<P>
Emperor Akihito, who presided over the ceremony, offered
condolences to the lives that were lost in the war and prayed for
world peace.
</P>
<P>
But in the Yasukuni shrine, a picture exhibition which lauded
the fighting spirit was held. However, few were deeply moved or
wept before those picture.
</P>
<P>
On the other side of the shrine, some right-wingers were trying
hard to sell their writings, including a title, "The Rape of
Nanjing is a Fabrication" -- another sheer distortion of
history. But few people bought those books.
</P>
<P>
The farce went to a high when eight Japanese ministers,
including Health and Welfare Minister Junichiro Koizumi,
International Trade and Industry Minister Shinji Sato, Transport
Minister Makoto Koga and Labor Minister Yutaka Okano visited the
shrine.
</P>
<P>
However, these ministers who were heavily escorted by police
paid very brief respect at the shrine, and left the scene as soon
as they finished praying.
</P>
<P>
It is worth mentioning that Japanese cabinet ministers' visits
to the shrine are controversial because Japan's postwar
Constitution stipulates separation of religion and the state.
</P>
<P>
The farce at the shrine ended in the evening and the rain
stopped. Although it was a farce, it reminded peace-loving people
to be on guard against a possible revival of militarism in Japan.
</P>
<P>
History cannot be distorted. Those people who seek to revive
militarism should remember an old Chinese saying: "A mantis trying
to obstruct a chariot has its body smashed to pieces." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
