<HEADLINE> Tajik Government Troops, Rebels Prepared for New Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Rebel Colonel Makhmud
Khudoiberdyev's brigade has set up a circular defense in the
stronghold of Kurgan Tyube, preparing for an imminent attack from
approaching government troops.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency quoted Khudoiberdyev as saying
government forces had advanced to the outskirts of Kurgan Tyube, a
town 110 kilometers south of the capital Dushanbe.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between Khudoiberdyev and deputy commander of the
Russian-led CIS peacekeeping force had failed. The agency said the
talks near Khudoiberdyev's headquarters in Kurgan Tyube lasted
only five minutes.
</P>
<P>
Reports said fighting renewed earlier today about 12 kilometers
southeast of Kurgan Tyube and the rebel colonel accused the
government of not withdrawing from Kurgan Tyube as agreed in
Wednesday's agreement.
</P>
<P>
He warned of "new spiral of the armed stand-off with
unpredictable consequences" if government troops failed to
withdraw immediately.
</P>
<P>
Fighting erupted between two warlords in Dushanbe last weekend,
only weeks after Rakhmonov signed a peace agreement with Islamic
opposition guerrillas aimed at ending four years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas were not involved in the latest clashes, but
Khudoiberdyev joined the fray, moving his brigade towards the
capital last Saturday. The motive for his latest mutiny -- his
third in two years -- remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
Khudoiberdyev, a motorized rifle brigade commander, was
dismissed from his post by Tajik President Imomali Rakhmonov on
Wednesday for leading the mutiny. He is believed to be the most
powerful military leader in the remote central Asian country.
</P>
</TEXT>
