<DOCNO> XIE19970816.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO to Help Great Lakes Countries Improve Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) signed a protocol today with the five countries of the
African Great Lakes region in a bid to intensify regional
cooperation for the improvement of health.
</P>
<P>
Under the protocol, Burundi, the Democratic Republic of Congo,
Rwanda, Tanzania, and Uganda will create inter-nation contingency
stocks of drugs and vaccines and establish an inter-nation
technical support team, WHO said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The five Great Lakes countries are to standardize case
management protocols, carry out joint operational research on
health problems of common interest, and hold regular meetings of
health officers.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to cooperate in epidemic prevention and the
control of infectious diseases with high epidemic potential, such
as cholera, epidemic meningitis, bacillary dysentery, measles,
viral hemorrhagic fevers, epidemic typhus, epidemic malaria,
plague, poliomyelitis and HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The WHO believes that cooperation between these countries can
help eradicate poliomyelitis in the region, while standardization
of treatment protocols of diseases, such as tuberculosis, will
permit refugees and other returnees to continue treatment in spite
of their migration.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to exchange information and create a pool of
experts that would be available immediately if needed. They also
agreed to set up an inter-nation contingency stock of drugs,
vaccines and other medical supplies that will permit rapid
response to epidemics.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly 10 percent of the population of these countries are
refugees or internally displaced people", WHO said. So diseases
linked to overcrowding, such as cholera, epidemic typhus,
bacillary dysentery and malaria, were easily spread.
</P>
<P>
"Partnership development and inter-agency cooperation is needed
more than ever," WHO African Regional Director Dr Ebrahim Samba
said at the signing ceremony in Kigali, Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is too vast...No single agency can effectively
control epidemics alone. It is not through the differences in
mandates, but through common interests that collaboration can be
expanded", said Samba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
