<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Displaced Burundians Facing Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of displaced
Burundians living in camps in the tiny central African country
are suffering from prolonged food shortage and malnutrition and
other diseases, the World Food Program (WFP) warned in a news
release received here today.
</P>
<P>
"In many camps, people have had restricted access to their
land and crops... They have missed two or three harvests. As a
result, nutritional problems are on the rise," said the news
release, quoting Benoit Thiry, Head of WFP Programming in
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 600,000 Burundians live away from their homes in
some 250 camp settlements throughout the country mainly due to
fighting in their villages. Many camps have inadequate sources of
clean water, poor sanitation facilities and little medical help.
</P>
<P>
Clinical signs of malnutrition with physical traits such as
wasting of body fat, swelling of the feet and lightness in hair
color -- have become prevalent in the camps over the last few
months, said the document.
</P>
<P>
"Generations of people could end up permanently blind, stunted
mentally or in extreme cases, dying of treatable diseases" in
Burundi due to long-term undernutrition, said Thiry.
</P>
<P>
Malnutrition rates are believed to be most acute in the
provinces of Karuzi, Bubanza and Kayanza of Burundi.
</P>
<P>
WFP has doubled its food aid assistance to the country for the
next five months with 21,000 tons of food to 280,000 of the most
vulnerable of the displaced Burundians, expecting to ease the
situation obviously.
</P>
<P>
The WFP food aid to Burundi will total 31 million U.S. Dollars
this year. The main donor countries are the United States and the
European Union members, the WFP Regional Information Office in
Nairobi told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at a press conference here today, the visiting
Burundian Minister of External Relations and Cooperation Luc
Bukingama said that Burundi had experienced "a very hard time"
due to the economic sanctions by the Great Lakes countries.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth rate in Burundi is negative now, compared
with around three percent in 1993 when the civil war broke out,
he added.
</P>
<P>
However, following a regional summit on the Burundi conflict
on April 16 in Arusha, sanctions on the country were dramatically
eased on food, medicine, agricultural inputs and construction
materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
