<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Wins, China Loses in Women's Volleyball GP HK Leg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champion Cuba won the
opening match while Olympic runner-up China lost to Italy on
Friday at the Hong Kong leg of this year's World Women's
Volleyball Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Cuba had no difficulties to beat Japan 14-3, 15-4, 15-6. It was
a sweet revenge over the Japanese who defeated Cuba 3-2 in the
earlier Seoul leg of the Grand Prix series.
</P>
<P>
China, ranked third after two earlier Grand Prix legs and had
won over Italy in the Macao leg last week, could not build a solid
defense and thus lost to the Italians 15-11, 15-10, 6-15, 4-15,
18-16.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Lang Ping said that her team defeat due to
the fact that the players failed to play to their form.
</P>
<P>
"The Italians, on the other hand, did a good job by jumpig high
and launching powerful spikes," Lang said. "They have long been
familiar with our style."
</P>
<P>
Speakng of Saturday's action against Japan, Lang said that the
Chinese had not faced the Japanese side ever since the Olympic
Games last summer in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
"We will play as we have planned," she said, declining to give
the details.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban team here includes only six players of its Olympians,
spearheaded by former captain Mireya Luiz.
</P>
<P>
"I'm satisfied with the match today. You could see the
improvement from the gap of the scores between the two teams, from
3-2 in Seoul down to 3-0 here," said Antonio Perdomo, coach of the
Cuban team.
</P>
<P>
The team still needed to improve in the combination of setting
and attacking in the future, he admitted.
</P>
<P>
Forseeing the team's clash against Italy Saturday, Perdomo said
that his team would win.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban team had won three out of its four matches against
the Italian in June this year.
</P>
<P>
Luiz said that she had enjoyed a six-month-long vocation after
the Atlanta Olympics, so she did not take long training before the
Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
The veteran said she would not go for the Olympic Games in
Sydney in 2000. "No, I don't think I'll go," she said. "I am too
old and there are so many jump players in the team that some even
can stand in my position now."
</P>
<P>
She also firmly denied the possibility of becoming a coach
after her retirement. But she declined to say what she would do in
that case. "I don't know," she just said.
</P>
<P>
On the tournament's second day on Saturday, Cuba takes on Italy
and China meets Japan.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Vittel Cup event here is one of the five legs for
the preliminary stages for this year's Grand Prix series. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
