<HEADLINE> Mugabe Calls for Bolstering of Indigenous Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe today challenged the country's financial institutions and
local authorities to work to ensure that interest rates are not
inhibitive to the development of indigenous businesses.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening a supermarket in Harare's Highfield high
density suburb, Mugabe said rigid policies by banks and local
authorities stifled entry into the mainstream economy by upcoming
black business people, most of whom lacked collateral security
and business premises.
</P>
<P>
"The banks should constantly review interest rates to ensure
they don't burden the indigenous people, and we urge the Harare
City Council to ensure its rates are not inhibitive to the
development of black-owned businesses," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there were still areas in major cities including
Harare's central business district which remained the domain of
white-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mugabe reiterated that the government would press
ahead with the land redistribution program which seeks to
resettle thousands of landless Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
He said, the government was consulting traditional chiefs in
all provinces trying to identify land for acquisition.
</P>
<P>
"If there is a white farmer who has built a dam or has made
other developments on the land, we will pay for those. But we
will not pay them for the land which they never paid,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
