<HEADLINE> Israel Refuses to Lift Closure on Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official
declared today that Israel will continue its open-ended "total
closure" imposed on the West Bank and Gaza Strip after Jerusalem
market bombing on July 30.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh told the state-run Israel Radio
that Israel will only ease the closure when the Palestinian
National Authority honors the Oslo Accords by clamping down on
terror.
</P>
<P>
The twin suicide bombings in Jewish west Jerusalem killed 15
people and wounded some 170 others.
</P>
<P>
Naveh claimed that meetings themselves are not enough and only
will have results when Israel considers to put an end to the
closure. He was apparently referring to the just-concluded shuttle
diplomacy by U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross between
Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
Ross wrapped up his four days of round-the-clock mediation
mission Wednesday with a Central Intelligence Agency
(CIA)-supervised mechanism in place to bolster Israel's internal
security by preventing terrorist operations from being launched
from the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly, at this point, have a beginning," he said, after
fifth and final meeting with Palestinian President Yasser Arafat
in Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Ross said that the achievement "makes it possible to do what is
essential -- settle the political differences."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright commented in
Washington that Ross' mission made headway on security issues and
she would come to the Middle East in the coming days or weeks.
</P>
<P>
However, Naveh's statement implied that Israel does not share
the U.S. assessment. Neither do Palestinian officials. Palestinian
Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath
responded that Ross had brought to the PNA nothing new and the
Palestinians would continue to suffer from the total closure.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli military authorities dropped the internal closure
on the West Bank cities of Ramallah and Hebron Thursday, leaving
only Bethlehem closed, while it opened a checkpoint in Gaza for
the export of goods.
</P>
<P>
The choice to keep Bethlehem closed is partly due to the
discovery of a bomb factory in nearby Beit Sahur a few weeks ago,
as well as the town's proximity to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu and Arafat Thursday continued to trade
accusations each other on terror issue. The Israeli prime minister
charged that the PNA is not fighting terror, which is a
condition for the continuation of the peace process. Arafat
responded by saying that Netanyahu was actually encouraging
terror. 
</P>
</TEXT>
