<HEADLINE> U.N.Security Council Considering Sanctions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan said today that the Security Council is right now
seriously considering sanctions against UNITA.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief made the statement at a press conference today
in Helsinki, without giving further details, the Angolan News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Annan also noted that he is making efforts to bring Angolan
President Eduardo Dos Santos and Jonas Savimbi, Chairman of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) back to
the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
Last month, President Santos expressed his willingness to meet
Savimbi on the condition that the venue should be on the Angolan
territory, and its capital to be exact.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said, the meeting must be focused on the
suspending issues of peace process, instead of those settled in
accordance with the Lusaka Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
Savimbi, on his part, argued that issues which have obstructed
the normal development of the peace process should top the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Peace Process is currently tied in a stalemate.
UNITA, the country's former rebel movement, had, under the
requirement of United Nations No. 1118 resolution reached on June
30, tabled two reports to the U.N. observation mission in Angola
before the organization's next session on Angola. But the result
is "unsatisfactory".
</P>
<P>
Annan noted today that it is still early to comment on UNITA"s
final plan. 
</P>
