<HEADLINE> Israel Attacks EU for Sending Letter to Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- In a move apparently aimed at
cold-shouldering the European Union, Israel has publicly lashed
out at the European position regarding the current
Israeli-Palestinian relations.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Israel Radio today quoted a Foreign Ministry
statement as describing as unacceptable EU's criticism of the
total closure imposed on the West Bank and Gaza Strip after the
Jerusalem suicide bombing on July 30.
</P>
<P>
The statement implied that the EU's ability to act as an
honest broker between Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) is questioned, according to the radio report.
</P>
<P>
The new crisis between Israel and the EU was triggered by a
letter sent by the multinational body's current president,
Luxembourg's Jacques Poos, to Palestinian President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said in a sour tone that "Poos refrained
from demanding that Arafat take practical steps against the
terrorist infrastructure."
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the U.S. stance, the EU president commented
that "Israel cannot expect the PNA to act against terrorism
because of its refusal to transfer tax revenues to the PNA even
though there is no basis for this in view of precedent."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry released the EU letter Thursday, a
move taken after U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross
concluded his four-day shuttle diplomacy, which focused on
pressuring the Palestinians to accept Israel's request for
security cooperation before resumption of peace talks. Ross's
pro-Israeli attitude was strongly slammed by Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
The EU letter also termed the measures enforced on the
Palestinians as "excessive." "The measures severely affect the
hardship of the Palestinian population although its responsibility
for the attack are not established," it added.
</P>
<P>
The message further stated: "The EU has decided to ask its
representatives in Tel Aviv to make a demarche upon Foreign
Minister (David) Levy to make our concern known." 
</P>
</TEXT>
