<HEADLINE> Zambia Urges SADC to Remove Border Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Vice President Godfrey
Miyanda urged here today the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) states to remove border barriers while
maintaining law and order, to enhance regional intergration.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening a SADC meeting on the free movement of
persons in the region, Miyanda said that while the region has
made recommendable strides towards the attainment of
intergration, the objective of achieving sustainable economic
growth and development will not be fully realized if people can
not move freely within the region.
</P>
<P>
These obstacles should be reduced to their minimum, if not
fully eliminated, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Miyanda advised the member countries to maintain
simple regulatory measures to maintain law and order because
leaving the borders too open to free movement of people will lead
to anarch.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the importance of creating an economic community
in the region, Miyanda said that if the region's small markets
remain fragmented, SADC will lose out in the new world economic
order. 
</P>
