<HEADLINE> Reports: Secret Documents on Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A leader of Israeli opposition
Labor party has unveiled two documents on the establishment of
Palestinian state reached a year ago between the party and the
Palestinians, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar organized by the Palestinian Research Center
Thursday, Yossi Beilin unveiled the documents as suggested
solution to the Palestinian crisis, MENA quoted Palestinian
newspapers published in Gaza today.
</P>
<P>
The documents were reached during secret negotiations between
Secretary of the Executive Committee of the Palestinian Liberation
Organization (PLO) Mahamoud Abbas and the then ruling Labor
party.
</P>
<P>
The documents stipulated the setting up of the Palestinian
state on the Gaza Strip and the West bank, Beilin said, adding
that according to the documents, only five percent of the West
Bank would be annexed to Israel.
</P>
<P>
This five percent of the West Bank would accommodate some
100,000 Jewish settlers, said Beilin.
</P>
<P>
The documents also stipulated that the capital of the
Palestinian state would lie outside the present border of
Jerusalem municipality, suggesting it to be in Abu Rudeis at the
outskirts of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Al Aqsa mosque would be placed under the Palestinian
sovereignty and the future status of Jerusalem would be discussed
later, on condition that the Palestinians recognize west Jerusalem
as the capital of Israel, according to the documents.
</P>
<P>
Beilin quoted PLO Secretary-General Abu Mazen as having said
that if such an agreement was reached the two parties would be
able to start final negotiations within one month.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace process has come to a stalemate
since the hard-line Likud group took power in May last year to
nullify the Labor's basic peace principles, especially the
land-for-peace formula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
