<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oklahoma Co-Defendant's Trial to Stay in Denver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. District Judge Richard
Matsch today turned down the request to move the trial of Oklahoma
City bombing defendant Terry Nichols from Denver, Colorado, to San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
In a three-page opinion, Matsch rejected arguments from
Nichols' attorneys that cite publicity surrounding the trial of
co-defendant Timothy McVeigh, 29, who was formally sentenced to
death by lethal injection Thursday, according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
Nichols is scheduled to go on trial on September 29 for bombing
the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building on April 19, 1995, which
killed 168 people and injured more than 500 people. Nichols faces
the same charges as McVeigh and could also face a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
Nichols' attorneys had suggested San Francisco for the trial,
contending media coverage of Timothy McVeigh's trial precluded
Nichols from finding an unbiased jury here.
</P>
<P>
Matsch, however, ruled they "failed to show a sufficient basis
for presuming such community prejudice as to require the requested
transfer to a different district."
</P>
<P>
Matsch said he had little trouble choosing a jury for McVeigh
and expects the jury selection process to go just as smoothly for
Nichols. 
</P>
</TEXT>
