<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Home Resales Up in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada's home resale market
pulled out of a lull in July, showing a month-over-month rise for
the first time since April, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Real Estate Association reported 19,011 existing
homes were sold in July, 3.5 percent more than in June, and 9.2
percent more than in July last year.
</P>
<P>
In May and June, resale numbers were lower than the previous
month, although they were higher than the same period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
"Sales are on a strong footing going into the second half of
the year," said Pierre Beauchamp, the association's chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
Full-time job growth and low mortgage rates will keep the sales
trend "on the rise" during the second half of the year, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Even if mortgage rates do creep up slightly between now and
the end of the year, they are likely to stay within a half a
percentage point of current levels," he said.
</P>
<P>
"That small an increase will do little to dampen activity," he
predicted.
</P>
<P>
"With jobs, consumer confidence and spending on the rise, sales
will be brisk over the autumn months," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
