<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Sankoh May Go to Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's former rebel
leader Foday Sankoh might be involved in talks to settle the
crisis in the troubled country.
</P>
<P>
The news came after a two-day meeting of West African foreign
ministers which ended today in Accra, capital of Ghana.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here quoted Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom
Ikimi as saying that Sankoh would possibly be included in a four
party negotiation for full settlement of the crisis in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting discussed Sankoh, who had been in
detention in Nigeria since March this year, and his Revolutionary
United Front (RUF) which fought successive governments in Sierra
Leone since 1991. Sankoh was invited to the capital Freetown by
the junta shortly after the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
Although Ikimi did not give any details, he said he "could not
rule out the possibility of Sankoh's being released and being
part of some final settlement along with the RUF".
</P>
<P>
The junta leader, self-appointed Head of State Major Johnny
Paul Koroma has named Sankoh as his deputy while keeping asking
Nigeria to release him.
</P>
<P>
Except Sankoh, said the report, foreign ministers from
Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire decided nothing new at
the meeting but to pursue the reinstatement of President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah ousted in the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
The other outcome of the meeting is they have prepared details
for the sanctions and embargo on Sierra Leone, which they will
submit to the summit of the the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) to be held later this month.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, representing the ECOWAS committee of four to
deal with the Sierra Leonean crisis, have so far held two rounds
of talks in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, with Koroma's delegation, in
an effort to persuade the junta to step down.
</P>
<P>
The first ended in mid-July with a ceasefire agreement between
ECOWAS peacekeeping force known as ecomog and soldiers loyal to
the junta. The second collapsed in session at the end of last
month when the junta said it would stay in power until the year
2001.
</P>
<P>
The junta's four-year transition plan also invited full-scale
sanctions from ECOWAS, which has announced a combination of
measures, dialogue, sanctions and use of force, to restore
Kabbah's legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
However, ECOMOG's limited military intervention, dialogue and
reinforced sanctions have failed to lead to the resolution of the
issue despite the fact that the measures do have created
tremendous difficulties to the junta.
</P>
<P>
Since thet crisis in Sierra Leone is regarded as posing threat
to peace and stability in the sub-region, people are waiting for
the coming ECOWAS summit to come out with solutions, may they be
peaceful campaign or military action.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
