<HEADLINE> Turkey Denies Postponement of War Games With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today denied the report
that a controversial Turkish-Israeli joint military exercise
scheduled to be held in the eastern Mediterranean in summer has
been postponed.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Turkish Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman
Sermet Atacanli was rejecting a report by Egypt's MENA news agency
on Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's comments of the war games.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a group of students in the northern Egyptian
province of Alexandria Wednesday, Mubarak said the Turkish-Israeli
maneouvre "gave the impression that Syria and Lebanon were meant."
</P>
<P>
"President Mubarak conveyed to Turkish President (Suleyman)
Demirel the fears and anxiety felt in the Arab nation. Turkey
decided to postpone the maneouvre," the MENA report said.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli's statement also pointed out that Turkey attaches
great importance to its ties with Egypt and supports development
in every field of the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Both presidents are expected to discuss bilateral relations
and regional issues when Demirel pays an official visit to Cairo
on September 16, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel announced earlier in May that they will
hold a joint military exercise in summer under the framework of
a cooperation agreement they signed in February 1996.
</P>
