<HEADLINE> Kenyan Currency Left to Defend Itself: CBK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior bank official today
said that the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) will leave the Kenyan
currency of shilling to defend itself in the local financial
market.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, CBK Governor Micah Cheserem
noted that the bank had refused to intervene to boost the weak
shilling.
</P>
<P>
The shilling remained weak on Friday after marginal gains to
close at 69.75 from 69.97, depreciating by 18.2 percent during
the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to exporters to bring in their export proceeds
promptly, not to expect that the shilling may depreciate further.
</P>
<P>
"Importers should not delay payment in the hope that the
shilling may appreciate in the coming weeks," he added.
</P>
<P>
His appeal was made following a dismal performance of Kenya's
treasury bill on Thursday due to the decision of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to suspend its Enhanced
Structural Adjustment facility to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The CBK only managed to auction 50 percent of the 200 million
U.S. Dollars worth of treasury bills offered at the stock market
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cheserem noted, "the shortfall is attributed to foreign
investors who have decided to liquidate their investments"
because of the recent lapse of the financial arrangement with the
IMF.
</P>
<P>
"The latest results of the treasury bill auction indicate that
some foreign investors have decided to liquidate their
investments and repatriate the proceeds," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The bank chief stressed that "despite the current challenges,
Kenya is still an attractive location for investment" as the
current interest rate is very lucrative.
</P>
<P>
"It will become even more attractive once the current
outstanding economic challenges are resolved," Cheserem added.
</P>
</TEXT>
