<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Round Cypriot Bi-Communal Talks Ends in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The second round of
U.N.-sponsored direct talks on Cyprus issue between President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash ended
in Montreux, Switzerland, today in deadlock, according to Cyprus
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Denktash was quoted as saying at a press conference after the
talks that the second round negotiations, which took place at the
Gighi Vaudois Hotel in Glion-sur-Montreux, ended in deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Denktash accused the European Union (EU) of having thrown a
"bomb" into the peace process by deciding to open accession
negotiations next year with Cypriot government, which is
internationally recognized.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader said talks on Cyprus' bid for EU
membership must be canceled for the U.N. mediation to continue.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides said in his statements that "at the end of
this week we are exactly where we were when we came here."
</P>
<P>
He rejected Denktash's accusation on the EU, saying that "not
only do I have no intention to delay the process but if there is
any interference in the process I will not be negotiating."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference later, U.N. Secretary-General's
Special Advisor for the Cyprus problem, Diego Cordovez, who
chaired the five-day talks between the two leaders of the two
Cypriot communities, said "they had useful discussion even when we
faced difficulties here in Glion."
</P>
<P>
He added, however, that the Secretary-General intends to
continue his good offices mission on Cyprus and said he does not
entirely share the view that "we are back to where we were when we
started."
</P>
<P>
Cordovez said he will submit his conclusions on this round of
talks to the U.N. Security Council next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first round of direct talks, the first meeting between the
two leaders since October 1994, was held between July 9 and 12 at
Troutbeck rural retreat, north of New York.
</P>
<P>
Before coming to Switzerland for second round talks, the two
leaders had two meetings in Cyprus, at the residence of the
U.N. Resident Representative Gustave Feissel, situated in the
U.N.-controlled Nicosia airport area, and reached an agreement on
humanitarian issues.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after the Turkish troops invaded and took over
the northern third in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite this island
nation as bi-communal, bi-zonal federation through peace talks,
but so far no tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970816.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
