<HEADLINE> Pan-African News Agency to Be Privatized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The board of directors of the
Pan-African News Agency (PANA) today agreed to revive the
money-strapped institution by turning it into a privately-owned
press company.
</P>
<P>
The board of directors of the PANA, which wound up its
extraordinary session here today, decided to allow national news
agencies of its member states to subscribe to PANA's capital, the
Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also decided to transform the real estate of the
PANA, about five percent of its capital, into shares that will be
distributed among PANA members according to their contributions.
</P>
<P>
The Dakar-based PANA is an inter-governmental institution of
news service which is affiliated to the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) and comprises news agencies of the OAU members.
</P>
<P>
The board of directors also accepted the membership of Libya,
South Africa, Kenya and Cote D'iviore today.
</P>
<P>
The plan for restructuring the regional news agency has been
under discussion for at least a year, with an emphasis on
maintaining its function as Africa's voice to the world and
information disseminator after it is privatized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
