<HEADLINE> Greek Cypriot Pilgrims Visit Monastery in Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Greek Cypriot
pilgrims visited the monastery of Apostolos Andreas on the tip of
the Turkish-controlled Karpass peninsula today to hold mass on one
of the holiest days on the Greek Orthodox calendar.
</P>
<P>
Around 620 Greek Cypriots, among them 47 are United Nations
employees, made the 150 kilometer, three-hour trek on
approximately 14 buses provided by the Turkish Cypriot authorities.
</P>
<P>
When they returned to the Ledra Palace check point in Nicosia
this evening, the pilgrims, many of whom come from the
Turkish-controlled areas, said they were very excited to see
their villages after 23 years.
</P>
<P>
They said they received warm welcome from Turkish Cypriots, who
expressed sincere desire for re-unification of the island.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish Cypriots wish for re-unification of Cyprus. They
offered us olive branches and flowers and were asking about their
own villages in the south," a Greek Cypriot pilgrim said, while
others stressed the need for rapprochement and more bicommunal
contacts.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 Turkish Cypriots were allowed last week to cross over
the U.N.-controlled ceasefire line to visit the Turkish Cypriot
enclave of Kokkina in the northeastern part of the island, about
five kilometers west of the Turkish occupied areas.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of visits was agreed by Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash during their
recent meetings in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders had two meetings in Nicosia last month, under
auspices of U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave
Feissel, and reached an agreement on humanitarian issues.
</P>
<P>
Last April some 450 Turkish Cypriots crossed to southern
government-controlled areas for a pilgrimage to Hala Sultan Tekke
mosque in Larnaca.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey sent troops
in and took over the northern third of the island following
a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
People from the two sides have been prohibited to cross the
180-kilometer-long U.N.-controlled buffer zone which separates
the island into two parts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
