<HEADLINE> Ottawa Sues B.C. over Testing Range Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada's federal government has
filed a lawsuit aimed at preventing British Columbia (B.C.)
province from shutting down a torpedo testing range, reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
If the B.C. government acts on its threat, the U.S. navy would
be forced out of the Nanoose Bay torpedo-testing range off
Vancouver Island next month.
</P>
<P>
B.C. Premier Glen Clark has said he will end the lease next
Friday unless the Canada-U.S. salmon quota dispute is resolved.
</P>
<P>
In a lawsuit filed in the Supreme Court of B.C., Ottawa argued
that the province has no right to make the move under a 1989
agreement with the federal government.
</P>
<P>
The agreement allows B.C. to terminate the lease after a 90-day
written notice. But cancellation can only take place if the
province requires the land for its own use.
</P>
<P>
"The province has failed to act reasonably and in good faith,"
the federal Justice Department said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
The shutdown will "frustrate the federal government's
fulfillment of its responsibilities in critical areas such as
national defense and international relations."
</P>
<P>
But Premier Glen Clark said he will not back down.
</P>
<P>
"I believe Canada has done a great disservice to British
Columbia and our ability to be successful on the salmon issue," he
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"It sends the wrong message to the Americans," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yet, some expert viewed the court action as a neutral way of
avoiding the lease cancellation while saving face for both sides.
</P>
<P>
"At first blush, it looks like it's turning up the heat, but
it's probably really putting it on the back burner," said
Professor Richard Paisley of the University of British Colombia.
</P>
<P>
That's because a court case could take years and both sides
could refuse to discuss it while it winds through the courts, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970816.0040 </DOCNO>
