<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- The United States increased its lead as the world's No. 1
weapons merchant, according to an annual arms survey published by
the Congressional Research Service. The American share of the
world's growing arms bazaar grew by nearly 23 percent last year,
to 11.3 billion U.S. dollars of the world's 31.8 billion U.S.
dollars market.
</P>
<P>
-- Researchers studying specimens from 3,000 people have
confirmed a genetic mutation that inhibits disease progression in
people infected with the virus that causes AIDS. Researchers
said that by pinpointing how these altered gens fight HIV, it
may be possible to develop treatments that help people delay the
on-set of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. involvement with Rwanda's military has been far more
extensive than previously disclosed, including psychological
operations and tactical Special Forces exercises that occurred a
few weeks before the start of last fall's Rwanda-led insurgency in
neighboring Congo, an internal Defense Department chronology
shows.
</P>
<P>
-- The three-member crew aboard the Russian space station got
off to a smooth start today on their mission to repair the
troubled craft. Cosmonauts Anatoly Solovyev and Pavel Vinogradov
along with U.S. astronaut Michael Foale circled Mir in a Soyuz
space capsule to inspect and videotape the station's damaged
exterior for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Times
</P>
<P>
-- The Dow Jones industrials plummeted almost 250 points
yesterday in a late wave of skittish selling that marked the worst
one-day point drop since the 1987 crash. The sell-off capped a
dizzying seven-day decline of 565 points, or almost 7 percent, from
record heights. 
</P>
