<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Mortgage Lenders Lift Rates to 5-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The mortgage war warmed up after
the Halifax, Nationwide and Woolwich, which together provide
mortgages for more than a third of Britain's borrowers, announced
0.25 percent increases in rates.
</P>
<P>
Halifax's new rate is 8.45 percent and takes immediate effect
for its new borrowers and from September 1 for its 2.5 million
existing borrowers.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth rate rise since the election, in line with
the 0.25 point rise in base rate announced last week, the highest
mortgage rate charged by the Halifax for nearly five years.
</P>
<P>
Halifax's announcement spurred its rivals Nationwide and
Woolwich to increase their mortgage rates, meaning that all the
major mortgage lenders have now put their rates up.
</P>
<P>
The rises also mean that a Halifax borrower with a 50,000 pound
(80,000 US dollar) interest-only loan will now pay 320 pounds (512
US dollars) a month, an increase of 9.48 pounds (15.17 US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
While a borrower with an identical mortgage from Nationwide
will pay 307 pounds (491 US dollars) a month, an annual saving
over the Halifax of 156 pounds (250 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Nationwide is offering lower mortgage rates than its main
rivals as part of a 200 million pound (320 million US dollar) bid
to promote mutuality.
</P>
<P>
The Halifax said house price inflation remained on target for 7
percent by the close of the year, and was expected to climb by a
similar amount next year.
</P>
<P>
Rising house prices are one of the inflation danger signs
warned by the Bank of England, along with rising retail sales,
lower unemployment and the impact of the 36 billion pound (57.6
billion US dollar) building society conversion windfalls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
