<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tops List in Arms Sales to Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States regained
the lead in selling arms to the developing world in 1996, almost
doubling the sales made by second-ranked Russia.
</P>
<P>
An annual report issued today by the U.S. Congressional
Research Service said the American share of the weapons market
rose by nearly 23 percent last year, to 11.3 billion U.S. dollars
in orders.
</P>
<P>
Total sales of American arms increased at a far more dramatic
pace to 31.8 billion dollars last year, up about 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. made 7.3 billion dollars in new weapons sales
contracts in 1996, representing 37.6 percent of all arms sales to
developing nations that year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has dominated the arms market in the developing world
over the past eight years. The nation has won 88.8 billion dollars
in new contracts, based on constant 1996 dollars adjusted for
inflation, from 1989 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Second-ranked Russia fell from its position as top seller in
1995 to second place in 1996, booking 3.9 billion dollars in new
sales.
</P>
<P>
Britain, which ranked fifth in 1995, boosted its ranking to
third in 1996 with contracts valued as 1.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
France ranked fourth in 1996 with 1.3 billion dollars worth of
contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
