<HEADLINE> Exports from Subic Bay Freeport Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Exports from the Subic Bay
Freeport in the northern Philippines hit 263 million U.S. dollars
during the first semester this year, a 66-percent increase over
the 158 million dollars recorded a year ago, a senior official
said today.
</P>
<P>
In a report to President Fidel Ramos, Richard Gordon, chairman
of the Subic Bay Metropolitan Authority (SBMA), said he was
confident that total exports from the freeport this year will
exceed 500 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gordon said that the steady increase in exports from the
freeport was a reflection of its stable economic condition and
investors' confidence not only in Subic but also in the entire
country.
</P>
<P>
Gordon said that he expects the export earnings to double in
the coming years when more companies in the freeport will start
opening.
</P>
<P>
Exports for June alone amounted to 56 million dollars,
representing an 80-percent increase from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Gordon also reported that the SBMA has finalized a
69-million-dollar loan agreement with the World Bank (WB) and the
Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund (OECF) to finance the expansion
of the Freeport.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to finance the construction of additional
infrastructure projects in the Freeport to accommodate more
businesses which have signified their intention to locate there,
he said.  
</P>
