<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Continue Poverty Alleviation Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
said today that the government will always pay great attention to
the poverty alleviation program under the presidential instruction
for the promotion of least-developed villages (IDT) program.
</P>
<P>
In his state address before the plenary session of the
parliament to mark the 52nd anniversary of the country's
independence on August 17, the president that the IDT program, now
entering its fourth year, is one of the country's high priority
programs.
</P>
<P>
He said the program has resulted to the lower number of people
living below the poverty line between 1993 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1996 national survey, the number of poor has
declined to around 22 million or about 11 percent of Indonesia's
population in 1996. In 1993, the poor people accounted for 14
percent of the total population.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto also said that the government has reinforced the IDT
program with a number of additional activities, such as the
supplementary food program for school children where priority is
given to villages covered by the IDT program, and the development
of rural infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
Starting this year, the poverty alleviation program was
intensified through the community welfare saving/credit program
which is concentrated in the non-IDT villages, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president said the poverty alleviation program is not the
only program for equitable distribution. What is also important is
the effort to promote small enterprises and cooperatives to become
strong and self-supporting businesses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
