<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China More Sophisticated in Market Circulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- China has had some progress in
reforming its distribution system, giving goods greater
accessibility to the market, especially in the five years since
the 14th National Congress of the Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
There were more than a thousand production materials and daily
necessities that were under State control, but the number has
dropped to about 30 now, and more than 85 percent of the country's
production of goods are based on market demand.
</P>
<P>
A multi-channel distribution system is taking shape, with
different forms of ownership competing. Last year, state and
collective enterprises accounted for less than 50 percent of
retail consumer sales, but for 95 percent of the means of
production.
</P>
<P>
A market pricing system has been formed, with 90-95 percent of
the prices under market regulation. China has more than 100,000
commodity markets, as well as auctions, second-hand goods markets,
leasing markets, and used vehicles markets.
</P>
<P>
A control system is also taking shape for major goods and
distribution puts equal value on the law of demand and State
controls, and keeps reserves of important commodities.
</P>
<P>
Governors are held accountable for the "rice bag", while mayors
assume responsibility for the "shopping baskets", to balance
supply and demand. As a consequence, the retail price index for
vegetables was 18.4 percent in 1996, relatively low, while that
for meat, poultry, and related products was 4.5 percent, a drop of
21.9 percentage points from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
New forms of distribution are emerging to give consumers more
conveniences. In 1995, China had some 150 chain-store businesses,
but the number was more than 1,700 at the end of last year,
accounting for more than three percent of consumer retail sales, a
new area of economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970816.0051 </DOCNO>
