<HEADLINE> Urgent: India's New Vice President Elected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Krishan Kant was elected vice
president of India today.
</P>
<P>
Krishan Kant, governor of Andhra Pradesh, was supported jointly
by the ruling United Front and the Congress and won 441 votes
while his rival, Surjeet Singh Barnala, backed by the Bharatiya
Janata Party and its allies, the biggest opposition in the
country, secured 273 votes.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the results, the returning officer, R.C. Tripathi
said here this evening that out of a total electoral college
strength of 779, 760 members had exercised their franchise.
</P>
<P>
Of the 760 votes polled, 46 were found to be invalid.
</P>
<P>
Krishan Kant is a school-and-college-friend of Prime Minister
Inder Kumar Gujral and is a veteran freedom fighter.  
