<HEADLINE> Philippine President Orders Probe of Sea Tragedies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos today
ordered a thorough investigation into Friday's two separate sea
tragedies in Manila Bay and a central Philippine strait which led
to the death of at least 19 people.
</P>
<P>
In a hand written memorandum, Ramos directed Transportation and
Communications Secretary Arturo Enrile to conduct a thorough probe
into the two sea accidents, one in Manila Bay and the other in
Biliran Strait in the central Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Enrile was asked to determine if the two vessels involved in
the two mishaps -- a small pleasure boat and an inter-land
passenger ferry -- violated the law on the safety of life at sea.
</P>
<P>
Ramos told Enrile to punish violators and submit a progress
report no later than August 19.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that both boats capsized due to strong
winds and big waves.
</P>
<P>
The passenger ferry overturned and sank in rough waters between
Maripipi Island and Kawayan, Biliran province, around 2:30 a.m.
Friday while the sight-seeing boat capsized off Manila Bay late
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A Coast Guard officer based in central Cebu city told Xinhua
tonight by telephone that 103 people have so far been rescued, 12
bodies recovered and 22 others remain missing or unaccounted for
in the Biliran sea accident.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Commander Crisolito Agustin, head of the Operation Division
of the regional coast guard based in Cebu, said the authorities
planned to stop the rescue operation by Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Agustin said he thought there is no more possible survivors due
to the strong winds and high waves on the mishap site.
</P>
<P>
In the Manila Bay tragedy, seven Hong Kong tourists were killed
and three Filipino crew members remain missing.
</P>
<P>
Reportedly, the two vessels did not have enough life vests and
the passenger ship was overloaded. Initial investigation showed
that the sight-seeing boat left on a cruise around Manila Bay
despite rough weather.
</P>
<P>
As the winds grew stronger, reports said, some passengers
demanded that the ferry return to port, but the boat capsized
before the crew could react.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
