<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Soccer Tournament Torn Apart by Armed Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- It is uncertain how the 29th
soccer tournament of Mogadishu would be concluded as the
semifinal matches were fired upon by jubilant football fans on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Three people were wounded after the armed football fans
supporting Gorgor Team used rocket propelled grenades and assault
rifles to attacked Mogadishu's main football stadium where a
soccer match was taking place on Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
When Benadir Telecom and Midnimo teams were competing for the
fourth post of the semifinals, the shooting occurred between the
stadium guardsmen and the Gorgor Team supporters annoyed by a
decision taken by the Somali Football Federation (SFF).
</P>
<P>
As the soccer tournament of Mogadishu's 12 first class
football teams is close to its final stage, Gorgor Team opposed
the decision by the SFF which gave 3 forfeit points to its
opponent team, Interglobe.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the supporters of Gorgor Team have distributed
leaflets to the Somali Olympic Committee, the SFF, the fans as
well as to the press, warning that no further matches could take
place in either of the two football stadiums in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
In a strong-worded leaflet two days ago, the Gorgor
administration said they won't shoulder the consequences if their
warning is defied and declared that violence will erupt if any
match is held at any of Mogadishu or Benadir stadiums in south
and north Mogadishu respectively.
</P>
<P>
Gorgor Team has also accused the SFF for partiality in its
decision favoring Interglobe.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a shooting has taken place in Mogadishu
Stadium since the unification of Somalia's Olympic Committee
which was affected by the long-standing anarchy in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a large congress held in North Mogadishu at the end of last
month, Somalia's Olympic Committee and its sports federations
were restructured with the approval of both faction leaders Ali
Mahdi Mohamed and Hussein Mohamed Aidid.  
</P>
</TEXT>
