<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mir Crew Fly in Space to Film Damaged Module </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Mir's three-man crew left the
space station Friday to videotape the damaged exterior which was
punctured in a space collision seven weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for a vital repair job, the two Russian
cosmonauts and their American colleague spent about 45 minutes
traveling round the orbiting station in a Soyuz spacecraft,
getting their first look at the damaged Spektr module, Itar-Tass
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The United States astronaut, Michael Foale, manned a video
camera and took photographs of the hull of the Spektr with a 500
millimeter zoom lens.
</P>
<P>
Space officials said they hoped the footage, filmed as the
Soyuz slowly sailed at a distance of 50 to 70 meters from the
module, would allow them to find the damage, which occurred in
June in a collision with a cargo vessel.
</P>
<P>
The crew plans to transmit the footage to Earth on Monday, and
technicians will spend several days analyzing it, said Mission
Control chief Vladimir Solovyov.
</P>
<P>
The cargo ship collision was the worst in a long series of
misfortunes to beset the Mir. Others included a fire, breakdowns
in the oxygen and cooling systems, and a severe power reduction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
