<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Tourists Leave Manila for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-seven Hong Kong tourists,
most of them survivors of the Friday ship capsize in Manila Bay,
left here at about 8:30 this evening for home.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the seven Hong Kong tourists drowned in the
accident were carried on the same flight.
</P>
<P>
But a little boy will stay here to wait for his Japanese father
to bring him home.
</P>
<P>
The tourists expressed heartfelt thanks to the Chinese embassy
for its prompt help in coping with the aftermath of the tragedy
and facilitating a smooth and quick return for them.
</P>
<P>
A Hon Kong tourist told reporters that only with the quick
reaction and the timely help from the embassy can they return home
so smoothly and quickly after being involved in such an unexpected
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese embassy sent personnel to Manila Bay to check the
situation shortly after learning of a pleasure boat carrying
mostly Hong Kong sightseers overturned late Friday afternoon in
the bay because of strong winds and big waves.
</P>
<P>
The embassy also acted quickly to provide clothes and food to
the survivors, who lost some of their personal belongs in the
accident. Embassy personnel were sent to the Manila Hospital to
take care of the survivors.
</P>
<P>
Charge d'affairs ad interim Sun Heping, on behalf of the
embassy, visited the survivors and expressed deep condolences to
them. He also worked together with the concerned Philippine
agencies in dealing with the accident.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a quick return of the tourists, the Chinese embassy,
with the permission from the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region government, issued travel permits to 10 survivors who lost
their passports in the mishap. The travel permits will be used as
passport.
</P>
<P>
The embassy also helped the tourists overcome other
difficulties, including translating the report on the accident
from Chinese into English, seeking help in preserving the bodies
of the dead and identifying the fatalities.
</P>
<P>
In Manila Bay, rescuers are still searching for the three
Filipino crew members who remain missing.  
</P>
