<HEADLINE> Recovering Sunken Warships In Yellow Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- China plans to raise three
warships that were sunk by the Japanese navy in 1895 in the Yellow
Sea, by October of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The ships were sunk during the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) in a
war with Japan, which left the Dynasty's entire fleet in ruins and
led to the signing of unequal treaties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
An official from the office overseeing the salvage work said
that after three months' efforts, salvage workers have spotted the
exact locations of the three warships near an island off Liaoning
province.
</P>
<P>
The salvage work will start next year, he said, as part of the
activities to mark the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
The Qing Dynasty's defeat in the sea battle one century ago is
regarded as a national humiliation.
</P>
<P>
China successfully raised a cruiser sunk by Japanese warplanes
in 1938 in the Yangtze River earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
