<HEADLINE> Nigeria Alerts on S. Leone Troops in ECOMOG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has announced the
military junta in Sierra Leone is kitting its soldiers in the
uniforms of the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) so as to
begin wanton destruction of lives and property.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Headquarters of Nigeria disclosed the plot on
Friday, two weeks ahead of a summit of the Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS) reported to take place on 28-29 of
this month.
</P>
<P>
An official statement described it as a ploy to blame the
sub-regional army for the destruction so as to whip up sentiments
and support from the international community against the ECOMOG,
which is in Sierra Leone for possible military action to restore
the civilian government toppled in the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
"The Sierra Leonean coupists had provided some segments of
their troops and rebel allies with ECOMOG troops uniforms
specifically to commence maximum wanton destruction of important
facilities, lives, properties and other nefarious activities," it
said.
</P>
<P>
"This action is aimed at generating condemnation of ECOMOG and
whipping up sentiments and support from the international
community and their relevant agencies," noted the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement also unvealed plans by the junta to poison the
ECOMOG's major source of water supply.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's discoveries came barely 24 hours after the Defense
Headquarters accused the junta of violating a ceasefire agreement
by attacking some ECOMOG positions in the troubled country and
assured the public of ECOMOG's capacity to continue to defend
itself.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu, reaffirming
Wednesday night's attack, said "We are not an occupation force
but we have a responsibility to protect our soldiers".
</P>
<P>
The junta also accused ECOMOG troops of attacking government
positions in Freetown's Lungi international airport on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
According to observers, the exchange of accusations may be
interpreted as moves taken by both sides to gain bargaining
counters for the coming ECOWAS summit, which is believed to focus
on a breakthrough of the impasse in Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
