<HEADLINE> Removing Illegal Posters From Chinese Streets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A campaign to get rid of illegal
posters and grafitti on walls was begun today in 100 Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
In the northeastern city of Harbin, thousands of young
volunteers worked along 1,486 streets to tear down illegal posters
and wash away large characters with the help of local residents.
</P>
<P>
In central China's Zhengzhou, some 2,000 youngsters got
involved in the activity, helping residents put up boards where
they can post notices legally and erased illegal advertisements in
public places.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 streets in east China's Nanjing city will be built into
"courtesy streets" according to an agreement reached between young
volunteers and local residents today.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the campaign is to improve people's morale and
lifestyle, just one of the series of activities for the opening of
the 15th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
