<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will build a
satellite launching center in Overberg in Western Cape Province,
a local daily Saturday Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
Western Cape Province is set to become the "Cape Canaveral", a
U.S. aerospace base, in the Southern hemisphere, earning the
region upward of 106 million U.S. Dollars a year and creating
hundreds of hi-tech aerospace jobs, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Houwteq, an aerospace division of South African commercial
giant Denel, is involved in negotiations with a major
international aerospace group which is keen to have its
satellites integrated and launched at the Houwteq site,,
Houwteq's divisional manager Ian Farr said.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiations are well advanced and we are confident that a
deal will be signed before the end of the year," Farr said. He
declined to identify the name of the aerospace group.
</P>
<P>
Houwteq had the capability to integrate, test and get an
average of 10 satellites ready for launch a year, according to
Farr.
</P>
<P>
"We will test, integrate and get the satellite and launch
vehicle ready for orbit at our site," Farr said.
</P>
<P>
Houwteq will run its satellite-launching facility in joint
ventures with other countries that will supply rockets from
sources such as Russia, which has many surplus launch vehicles
after its post-Cold War disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Several international satellite groups recently visited the
Houwteq site and the Overberg launch facility, the report said,
adding that British Aerospace, Sweden and the Czech Republic had
already used the facility for aviation and other tests.
</P>
<P>
South Africa developed an advanced space program in the early
1990s, successfully launching three rockets into space during the
test phase.
</P>
<P>
However, pressure from the United States and the escalating
cost of the 1.06 billion Dollar space project forced the country
to scrap its rocket development program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
