<HEADLINE> Mubarak Condemns Lopsided Pressure on Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
has called on the United States to put pressure on Israel rather
than the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) only, saying that it
is unfair to show severity to PNA President Yasser Arafat alone.
</P>
<P>
In an interview front-paged in today's Al-Ahram, a leading
Egyptian daily, Mubarak, a staunch supporter of the Palestinian
cause, warned against negative consequences of weakening the
position of Arafat.
</P>
<P>
"If Arafat is gone, inter-Palestinian acute problems will erupt
and a state of anarchy will ensue, dealing a death blow to the
peace talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said progress in the Arab-Israeli negotiating process
is the way to stop violence in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Security coordination, highlighted by Israel, is not
everything," he added in the interview.
</P>
<P>
After the July 30 suicide bombings in Jerusalem which killed 15
Israeli civilians, Israel clamped a series of security measures
including travel ban and economic sanctions on the Palestinians
and demanded a firmer Palestinian hand on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He told the Arabic daily that closure of Palestinian self-rule
areas and Israel's anti-Palestinian mass punishment measures might
cause more violence than before.
</P>
<P>
Describing the stand of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu as "unbalanced," Mubarak said the Likud leader has to
abide by his peace commitments to encourage the Palestinians to
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has urged Israel to ease the sanctions against the
Palestinians but apparently accepted Israel's insistence on seeing
the Palestinians give evidence of renewed security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The president also showed caution to a proposed summit bringing
him with Arafat, Netanyahu and Jordan's King Hussein together,
which will possibly be sponsored by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright during her upcoming visit to the region.
</P>
<P>
"Lack of good preparation and, consequently, failure of such a
summit, would lead to negative results and fuel frustration," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt had failed to mediate an end to the Palestinian-Israeli
crisis before an intense four-day shuttle diplomacy of U.S. peace
envoy Dennis Ross helped re-establish security talks between
intelligence officials of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Albright had announced she planned to make her first trip to
the region, probably in September to push across a major U.S.
peace initiative that will focus on accelerated talks on a final
peace settlement and implementation of the existing
Israeli-Palestinian agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
