<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Not to Increase Oil Output: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has denied it
threatened to increase oil output in retaliation for Latin
American oil exporter Venezuela's violation of its quota within
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
"Threatening or warning is not how we operate," said Prince
Abdelaziz Bin Salman Bin Abdul-Aziz, Saudi petroleum
undersecretary, quoted by Riyadh-based Arabic daily Okaz today.
</P>
<P>
The prince was commenting on an article in the U.S. Wall Street
Journal Friday claiming Saudi Arabia sounded the threat during a
meeting between him and the head of a Venezuelan oil firm on the
sidelines of OPEC ministerial conference in Vienna last June.
</P>
<P>
The prince said that during that meeting they examined the
launching of joint investment ventures between the two countries,
including in the field of oil refining.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, one of OPEC's 11 members, now produces 3 million
barrels of crude per day (bpd), exceeding its quota of 2.29
million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's top oil producer and exporter, pumps
out slightly more than 8 million bpd. It has about one fourth of
the world's total proven oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's oil production ceiling stands at 25.03 million bpd. But
as member countries increased yield starting last November, its
daily output reached 27.05 million barrels in April this year,
about 2 million barrels above the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
This 8 percent surplus of production, however, forced oil
prices in the world markets to decline by 20 percent in the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's oil ministers formally endorsed in Vienna June 26 a
quickly-concluded accord including a roll-over until the year end
of the notional production ceiling of 25.03 million barrels a day,
intending to tell the world oil markets they are serious about
cutting back oversupply to reverse a downtrend in crude
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
