<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Not Happy with Continued Decline in Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today expressed his unhappiness with the
continued decline in the value of the country's currency ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit, together with Indonesia's rupiah, the Thai baht
and the Philippine peso, fell sharply against the U.S. dollar in
recent weeks due to strong currency speculation.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is discussing with other members of ASEAN faced with
the same problem to seek ways to deal with the matter, Mahathir
told reporters here after opening the 26th delegates conference of
Gerakan, a component party of the ruling National Front led by
Mahathir.
</P>
<P>
He said the central banks in the region, including Malaysia's
Central Bank, have been in "some communication" with each other.
</P>
<P>
On whether the central banks in the region would get together
to fight the decline in the value of several ASEAN currencies, he
said "We see what we can do... We have some communication."
</P>
<P>
To a question on if he was still happy with the level of the
ringgit, Mahathir said "of course, I am not happy. I want the
ringgit to go back to an acceptable level."
</P>
<P>
However, the Malaysian leader said his country will come out of
this some how. "We have got confidence we can manage our economy,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said due to the so-called "open economy", the rich
countries today have found a way of subverting the poor countries.
</P>
<P>
"Everything is in their favor. They have the money (and) they
can subvert us. We work for 14 years trying to build up the
economy and these people come and rob poor people," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE), Mahathir said that
local investors and fund managers must protect the KLSE and
maintain the prices of the counters or "otherwise they will lose".
</P>
<P>
"We already lost more than 200 billion ringgit (about 74
billion U.S. dollars) which is equivalent to about four years of
our national budget and this is because the robbers come and
undermine our economy," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
