<HEADLINE> Indian PM Reiterates Liberalization Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral today reiterated his government's determination to
continue liberalization policy pursued in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the national conference of "50 years of Indian
industry -- the challenges for the future", organized by the
Confederation of Indian Industry (CII) here, Gujral said that
after 50 years of political independence, the country should work
for economic independence.
</P>
<P>
There would be no turning back from the policies of
liberalization. The reform in India did not hang in air, he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his government's commitment to investment oriented
policies, particularly in the infrastructure sector, the prime
minister said that it was time for private investors to
participate in the core sector.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Outsiders (foreign investors) are welcome, but will
not be allowed to drown us. They are welcome but will not be
allowed to takeover. They will invest in sectors where we need
them."
</P>
<P>
He said this in an obvious bid to allay the Indian industry's
fears of multinationals swamping them.
</P>
<P>
He warned against any complacency on the economic growth front,
saying "without growth we are doomed. Growing population and
increasing unemployment have to be looked in totality."  
</P>
</TEXT>
