<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange were lower this week.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the Composite Index, which tracked 100 quality
stocks, sagged to a low of 885.22 before recovering to a high of
929.50. It ended the week 22.18 points lower than 910.18 last
week.
</P>
<P>
The all main board share Emas Index lost 8.0 points to 261.99
and the Industrial Index lost 15.01 points to 1,865.56.
</P>
<P>
On Friday afternoon, the local currency ringgit hit a
historical low of 2.8250 against the U.S. dollar since it was
officially floated in 1973, on speculative attacks.
</P>
<P>
To check against the impact of a weaker ringgit and correct the
country's external account imbalance, Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim's announcement that the government may
consider deferring national projects which are not considered
"critical," and try to boost exports through budgetary measures
are most welcome by economists, analysts and the business people.
</P>
<P>
However, it failed to boost confidence in the stock market
badly battered by liquidation by foreign players.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad Friday called upon
local investors to dominate the exchange.
</P>
<P>
Three counters were listed on the second board this week, with
PPB Oil Palms, whose initial share offer price was 2.80 ringgit,
ending the week at 2.87 ringgit, General Soil whose initial share
offer price was 2.70 ringgit, settling the week at 7.25 ringgit
and Ocean Capital whose initial share offer was 3.00 ringgit,
closing at 5.80 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The weekly main board ready turnover rose to 1.243 billion
shares worth 5.624 billion ringgit from 1.065 billion shares
valued at 7.430 billion ringgit last week.
</P>
<P>
The Second Board turnover was 258.690 million shares worth
2.496 billion ringgit from 186.816 million shares valued at 1.938
billion ringgit last week.
</P>
<P>
Off market deals amounted to 149.683 million shares worth
895.446 million ringgit from 149.936 million shares valued at
1.338 billion ringgit last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
