<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of crude
palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week all
higher.
</P>
<P>
Demands for palm oil improved this week as the ringgit
continued its bearish note, which closed at 2.7830/50 a U.S.
dollar against 2.6500/30 last week.
</P>
<P>
August South sharply increased by 47.50 ringgit to 1,295
ringgit (about 470 U.S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
Players expect CPO physicals to move up next week, adjusting to
the ringgit factor. Analysts felt that the local unit would
continue to remain weak in the near term.
</P>
<P>
The Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) also closed higher at 14.65
ringgit (5.4 dollars) per kg against 14.52 ringgit (5.3 dollars)
per kg last week.
</P>
<P>
"Demands for the local tin improved on the ringgit's weakness
as it was considered cheap for overseas buyers," a trader said.
</P>
<P>
Players ignored the weak movement on the London Metal Exchange
(LME), which witnessed a sharp fall since early in the week, as
the local market was dominated by the currency factors.
</P>
<P>
Accumulated turnover of the week narrowed to 743 tons against
914 tons last week.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM price differential to that of the LME stood at a
discount of 15 dollars per ton against a discount of 5 dollars
last week.
</P>
<P>
Trader said the value of the ringgit to the U.S. dollar will
determine the prospects of demand for local tin next week, but
further uptrend is likely as the local currency seemed to retreat
further.
</P>
<P>
On the Malaysian rubber market during the week, Malaysian
rubber showed some signs of price recovery on the weakening of the
ringgit.
</P>
<P>
The rubber price which once hit its low of 228.00 sen (84 U.S.
cents) per kg for the RSS grade in mid-July, in dull trading,
closed at 250.50 sen (92 U.S. cents) per kg compared to 247.50 sen
(91 U.S. cents) per kg last week.
</P>
<P>
At the week's close, demands also improved, especially for the
nearby month which adjusted to the currency factor.
</P>
<P>
Steadier movement on the Tokyo market also spurred the bullish
sentiments in the market this week, despite surplus production in
Indonesia and Thailand, which still sell their rubber below the
market price.  
</P>
</TEXT>
