<HEADLINE> Soeharto Calls for Addressing Challenges in Open World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKAKTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
today called on the people to be ready to address challenges and
seize new opportunities in an open global economy and free trade
era.
</P>
<P>
In his state address at the parliament here today to mark the
52nd anniversary of the country's independence, the president said
the world seems to become a huge economic entity.
</P>
<P>
"We live in a fast-changing world. Quite often what takes place
in a country or region will immediately have an impact on anther
country or region," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The main challenge remains to be how these fundamental on-going
changes can be transformed into the establishment of a new world
order which is more peaceful, equitable and prosperous for all, he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the current changes in the world can bring a
beneficial but also an adverse impact on economy and development,
especially in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"What we have to do is to capitalize on the beneficial
influences, on the one hand, and to minimize as little as possible
whatever damaging influences to our national development,"
stressed the president.
</P>
<P>
He held that the recent upheavals affecting the currencies of
several countries in the Southeast Asian region have been a
concrete evidence of the adverse impact of an open global economy.
</P>
<P>
Currencies of some Southeast Asian countries including
Indonesia have depreciated against the U.S. dollar since early
July.
</P>
<P>
He said, the speculative actions by certain individuals have
worsened the situation and raised the market sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
"The recent experience has taught us a valuable lesson that in
a situation full of uncertainties and upheavals, the economic
fundamentals conditions is very important and decisive," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized the importance of closer relations amongst
nations to face regional and international monetary upheavals.
'Not a single country is immune to them. Not a single country will
be able to brave these global waves."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
