<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economic Growth Reaches 7.98 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
said today that his country's economic growth in 1996 reached 7.98
percent, higher than the earlier provisional estimate of 7.82
percent.
</P>
<P>
In his state address on the occasion of the 52nd anniversary of
Indonesia' independence before the parliament here today, the
president said with such an economic growth and the population
growth rate of 1.58 percent, Indonesia's per capita income has
reached 1,155 U.S. dollars, 16 times higher compared to the figure
of 1969.
</P>
<P>
Until the third year of the current Sixth Five-Year Development
Plan (1994-1999), Indonesia's economy has grown with an average of
7.9 percent annually, he said, adding that it is quite high
compared to the average goal of 7.1 percent for the period.
</P>
<P>
The high economic growth was spurred by the great enthusiasm in
investment. In the past 1996-97 fiscal year, the approved domestic
investment reached more than 105 trillion rupiah (42 billion U.S.
dollars), an increase of 20 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The number of approved foreign investments continues to be
high, totalling 26.6 billion dollars, although not as high as the
previous year with 39 billion dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
In line with the industrialization process, Soeharto said that
the share of the agricultural sector in the national product is
expected to continue to decline. However, its share in the economy
remains extremely vital, as a source of foodstuffs, as basic
materials for industry and also as a source of income for millions
of farmers.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that the non-oil/gas industry has
grown at an average of 12.8 percent annually during the three
years of the current five-year plan, making the industry the motor
of development.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, the country's economic stability is
demonstrated by, among other things, the controlled inflation rate
and the foreign exchange reserves that are maintained within a
safe limit.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Indonesia's inflation rate was still 9.2 percent. It
was lowered to 8.6 percent in 1995 and 6.5 percent in 1996. It is
expected to reduce to 5.2 percent in 1997, said the president.
</P>
<P>
Although the current account deficit is expanding, Soeharto
said, the balance of payments remains safe as a result of the
substantial inflow of capital.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the country's current account
deficit will reach 9.8 billion dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's foreign exchange reserves is estimated
at 21 billion dollars. The potential of foreign exchange reserves
to finance import has increased from 4.6 months at the end of
1995-96 to 5.5 month last July, said the president.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
