<HEADLINE> Singapore to Revamp Policies to Face Global </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Senior Minister Lee
Kuan Yew hold that the government should revamp its policies in
major economic sectors to face the keener global competition and
the result of breakthroughs in technology, especially information
technology, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at a local National Day celebration dinner Friday
night, the minister said that for the last one year, the
government has been doing a stock-taking and an audit of
Singapore's position in the context of regional and international
developments.
</P>
<P>
"Global competition is keener, and our competitiveness is under
challenge," Lee said, "One result of this re-examination of our
challenge is the need for a better and differently trained
workforce, one able to respond to the changes in information
technology."
</P>
<P>
"Education and training are the decisive factors," he stressed,
"it is the software we put into our people."
</P>
<P>
Taking the financial market in Singapore as an example, Lee
said that in order to compete with other financial centers like
Hong Kong, Singapore must "try to be a bigger business center for
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) businessmen, for
the top ASEAN companies, just like Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"We have to be a cosmopolitan Asian city for all peoples from
the world over, Americans, Europeans, Arabs, and Asians," he
urged.
</P>
<P>
The senior minister also called on the Singapore Airlines to
become "globally competitive" and warned that if it failed to do
so, "it will decline."  
</P>
</TEXT>
