<HEADLINE> SADC Adopts Documents on Peace, Defense, Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A ministerial meeting of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) has adopted three
documents on peace, defense and security, according to the local
press today.
</P>
<P>
Local press today reported that these documents were adopted
at the one-day meeting held here Friday after "extensive
discussions" by 17 ministers of foreign affairs, defense and
security from the SADC's 12 member states.
</P>
<P>
The documents outline the organization's institutional
guidelines, which seek to promote lasting peace, security and
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Stan Mudenge, Zimbabwe's Foreign Minister and chairman of the
meeting stressed that the three documents will promote
cooperation among member states and help settle intra-state and
inter-state conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The ministers present at the meeting agreed that regional
cooperation is a prerequisite for economic development and unity
among the SADC's members.
</P>
<P>
The documents will be submitted for consideration and approval
to the heads of states at the next yearly summit.
</P>
<P>
AT the meeting, the ministers also exchanged their views on
regional peacekeeping, the U.N. reforms and conflicts in Angola.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed regional support for the Angolan peace
process, which put an end to the country's several decades of
civil war, and called upon the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), a major opposition party, to
abide by its relevant commitments to realise peace in the
country. 
</P>
