<HEADLINE> Kenya Ready to Negotiate with IMF Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is
willing and ready to resume "tough negotiations" with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) over the lapsed key loan,
Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) Governor Micah Cheserem has claimed.
</P>
<P>
Kenya is considering re-opening talks with IMF for the
remaining two-year arrangement of the 215-million-U.S.-Dollar
three-year loan offered under the Enhanced Structural Adjustment
Facility (ESAF), he was quoted by today's Kenya Times as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has implemented far-reaching economic
reforms in the last four years, said Cheserem, pleading foreign
investors not to "abandon Kenya in view of the current problems."
</P>
<P>
The Washington-based IMF suspended on August 1 its key loan to
Kenya, citing high-level corruption as a key reason.
</P>
<P>
The IMF loan suspension immediately created panic at the
Nairobi Stock Exchange and the Shilling has continuously taken a
downward spiral, although the CBK has so far pumped in some 100
million Dollars sold to commercial banks to stabilize the shock,
</P>
<P>
Cheserem said on Friday his bank would leave the shilling at
the mercy of the market forces and would only move in to cushion
dramatic changes.
</P>
<P>
The Shilling remained weak on Friday after marginal gains to
close at 69.75 from 69.97 against U.S. Dollar, depreciating by
18.2 percent during the past two weeks. 
</P>
