<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's diamond
giant De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd has announced that it will
move to prevent foreign diamond mining companies from snapping up
mining properties it had sold to black South Africans.
</P>
<P>
"We were a little disappointed that one, maybe more of the
property that we sold have in fact been on-sold to Canadian
companies," local daily "The Citizen" quoted De Beers diamond
consultant Gareth Penny as reporting today.
</P>
<P>
This had created unwelcome competition and De Beers was now
considering introducing a buy-back clause on property sold, Penny
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Penny, De Beers had earlier this year reviewed
all its mining properties and identified 50 that were suitable
for small black-owned mining companies.
</P>
<P>
"We put those out for sale earlier this year and we were very
pleased that we managed to sell 44," Penny said.
</P>
<P>
South African Minerals and Energy Minister Penuell Maduna
recently criticized large mining groups for monopolizing mineral
rights and sitting on properties rather than developing them.
</P>
<P>
Maduna hinted that he might change the present system of
mineral rights to ensure that more black groups became involved
in mining. 
