<BODY>
<HEADLINE> T-shirt Dyes Might Pose Cancer Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Consumer Council
warned that a chemical used to dye clothes might cause skin
cancer, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Azo dyes, which contain banned chemical benzidine, were found
on four T-shirt samples out of 44 bought from outlets in Hong
Kong, today's South China Morning Post quoted the Council as
saying.
</P>
<P>
All four samples were bought from street hawkers and had no
labels, making it impossible to trace their origin, while the rest
of the samples, all purchased from department stores, were judged
safe.
</P>
<P>
There is no law prohibiting the use and sale of azo dyes, which
can be made from alternative safer chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Consumer Council said that there was no
scientific consensus on the health-status of azo dyes. A new study
in the Netherlands warned of possible danger in the use of azo
dyes, while a U.S. test in 1983 said azo dyes posed no health
risk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
