<HEADLINE> Plavsic's Decision on Parliament Challenged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Serb President Biljana
Plavsic's decision early last month to dissolve the parliament was
challenged today by the constitutional court.
</P>
<P>
The court in Pale, capital of the Serb Republic of Bosnia and
Herzegovina, announced its ruling after days of deliberations
beginning from Tuesday, said a Tanjug news agency report.
</P>
<P>
The ruling held that Plavsic's decision on July 3 to dissolve
the parliament and hold a new parliamentary election on September
1 did not conform to the constitution of the Serb Republic.
</P>
<P>
However, in a televised speech tonight, Plavsic declined to
comment on the court's ruling and said she was yet to receive an
official statement from the constitutional court.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic has recently run into serious disputes with the
parliament on some important issues, and her decision to dissolve
the legislative body is seen as a move to dump the opposition.
</P>
<P>
In its response, the Bosnian Serb government, which has been on
the parliament's side in the disputes with Plavsic, sued the
president at the constitutional court on July 7. 
