<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maritime Public Security Alarm System In Southeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- A maritime public security alarm
system in China's Fujian province has begun work, the second
coastal area in China, after Hainan province, to use it, according
to Colonel Wang Changtai, vice commander of the Fujian Provincial
Frontier Guards.
</P>
<P>
Favorable natural conditions and a vast offshore area with a
3,300-km coastline, and 1,400 islands and 2,120 ports provide a
great boost to the province's economy.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, they also provide a good place for marine crime,
which is on the increase, everything from blockade running,
smuggling, and plundering to murder.
</P>
<P>
Taking a tip from the model police forces in Zhangzhou city,
the Fujian maritime frontier guards decided to set up a maritime
public security system.
</P>
<P>
The alarm system is expected to help control violent crime,
maintain maritime public security, and assist other departments
with marine incidents, Colonel Wang explained, adding that the
system will be first used by the First Maritime Armed Police
Detachment, and then expanded next year to two other
detachments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
