<HEADLINE> Finding Foster Homes For Southwest Chinese Orphans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Zhu Wenjie, who became the
foster mother of a year-old orphan in Guilin in China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region is one of 30 people who have volunteered
to care for abandoned children in this scenic tourist spot.
</P>
<P>
World Vision, the international charitable organization, has
worked with local social welfare institutes to develop this
program, providing financial support for the foster mothers, who
must have sufficient living space, a healthy family life, and
hygienic conditions for the adopted orphans.
</P>
<P>
They must also prove that they and their family members have no
criminal record.
</P>
<P>
The head of World Vision visited Zhu and her new daughter
recently, and the 45-year-old foster mother said, "When I saw the
advertisement of the social welfare institute, the idea of
adopting an orphan came to my mind," explaining that she felt very
lonely after her retirement.
</P>
<P>
"I have deeply loved children since I was very young," she
said, and her own children are grown and work for themselves.
</P>
<P>
Since the adoption in March, the Guilin Social Welfare
Institute has checked monthly on the conditions of the 30 orphans.
</P>
<P>
According to officials, the program will be expanded to other
cities and counties in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
