<DOCNO> XIE19970816.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Holds Off Military Ally Status for Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today held off granting Argentina the status of
an ally outside the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before meeting here with visiting
Argentine Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella, Albright said she and
her Argentine counterpart would discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
"This is the kind of decision that requires consultation with
Congress," she added. "There is no announcement being made."
</P>
<P>
However, the top U.S. diplomat noted that Argentina is "one of
the closest friends and partners the United States has in this
hemisphere and around the world."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Albright said the United States is planning to
grant the status to Argentina. "The announcement has not yet been
made but we do wish to recognize Argentina role," she said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Foreign Assistance Act of 1961, the U.S. president
has the right to designate close military allies, a status that
does not require U.S. help in case of attacks, but allows the
allies to buy excess weapons from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Countries already designated as close non-NATO U.S. allies are
Israel, Egypt, Jordan, Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here said the granting of the status to Argentina is
expected to be announced by U.S. President Bill Clinton when he
visits Argentina in October.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration last week lifted a ban on the sale
of high-tech arms to Latin America. The ban was imposed in the
1970s when most countries in the region was under military rule.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the moves by Washington in Latin America are
designed to compete with France, Russia and other European
countries for the arms market in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
