<HEADLINE> CMIE Foresees Growth of Indian Industrial Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The industrial production is
expected to grow by about four to five percent in the first half
of 1997-98 fiscal year (April 1,1997-March 31,1998) and thereafter
pick up to around eight percent, sources from the Center for
Monitoring Indian Economy (CMIE) said here today.
</P>
<P>
The 1997-98 fiscal year is likely to end with a growth of six
to seven percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1996-97, Indian industrial production registered 6.6 percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
Based on the statistics by the Industry Ministry for 24
industries which account for 50.37 percent of the weight in the
official index of industrial production, the private think-tank
asserted that the overall growth of the industrial production was
2.8 percent in April and 4.9 percent in may,1997. The growth
during the first two months of this fiscal year came mainly from
fertilizers, aluminum and textiles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
