<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Bars Foreign Trading Houses From Retail Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government is
likely to give conditional approval for foreign trading houses to
set up wholly-owned subsidiaries in certain specific sectors, but
will not allow them to enter into the retail business, official
sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a recent meeting here, the Foreign Investment Promotion
Board (FIPB) decided to permit wholly-owned subsidiaries of
foreign trading houses to undertake exports and imports in line
with export-import policy specifications.
</P>
<P>
But the board agreed to bar trading houses with 100 percent
foreign equity from the retail business due to opposition from the
domestic industry, especially the small sector. Many corporations
said this would result in such companies importing consumer goods
from the principles abroad and selling them in the retail market.
</P>
<P>
The FIPB has put on hold for the past four months a dozen
proposals by Japanese and American multinationals to establish
trading houses here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
