<HEADLINE> Govt Ready to Help Carpet Industry: Nepali PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The government is ready for
discussions with the carpet industry to further promote its
development, Nepali Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand said.
</P>
<P>
The carpet industry which is Nepal's top exporter has been
making a significant contribution to the economy by earning
foreign exchange and providing jobs, Chand said Friday when
inaugurating the annual general meeting of the Central Carpet
Industry Association (CCIA).
</P>
<P>
During the first 11 months of last fiscal year which ended on
July 14, Nepal produced about 2.7 million square meters of carpet
and earned some 150 million U.S. dollars, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
About 250,000 Nepalese depend on the industry for livelihood.
</P>
<P>
The number of carpet enterprises affiliated to the CCIA has
reached 844.
</P>
<P>
Although false publicity had brought about some slump in the
carpet industry in the past, there now seems to be a turnaround,
Chand said, adding that what the industry needs is improvement in
quality and market diversity.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister is referring to the alleged involvement of
child labor in the carpet industry, which has led to a decline in
export.
</P>
<P>
Besides, low quality and use of the hazardous azo dyes are also
among the main problems facing Nepalese carpet industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
