<HEADLINE> Exports From Philippine Economic Zones Soar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Exports from the Philippines'
dozens of economic zones soared 132.7 percent to 6.40 billion U.S.
dollars in the first half of the year from 2.75 billion dollars a
year ago, according to a government report published here today.
</P>
<P>
Exports from the four government-run economic zones expanded by
more than 23 percent to reach 2.18 billion dollars during the
first semester, said the report issued by the Philippine Economic
Zone Authority (PEZA).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, shipments from private economic zones increased by
331 percent to 4.2 billion dollars from the 978 billion dollars
recorded a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Shipments from the economic zones accounted for more than half
of the Philippines' 11-billion-dollar exports during the same
period, the report said.
</P>
<P>
For the month of June alone, shipments from the state and
private industrial estates amounted to 2.5 billion dollars, a
135-percent jump from May.
</P>
<P>
PEZA Director General Lilia de Lima attributed the robust
growth to the increased number of locators in the special economic
zones as well as the recovery of the global electronics sector.
</P>
<P>
The country has so far established 54 economic zones, of which
only four were run by the government. The economic zones have
become a major foreign exchange earner for the Philippines during
recent years.
</P>
<P>
The economic zones earned the Philippines 6.5 billion dollars
in export receipts in 1996, accounting for 32 percent of the
country's total export earnings that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
