<HEADLINE> Clinton Discusses Arresting Karadzic With Senior Aides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today discussed with top foreign policy officials the necessity of
apprehending former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, who is
indicted by Washington and its allies as a war criminal.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after Clinton met with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and U.S. envoy to Bosnia Richard Holbrooke, White House
spokesman Michael McCurry stressed the importance of putting
Karadzic on trial.
</P>
<P>
"It's very important for all the parties to make good the
commitment specifically expressed in the Dayton accords, that he
and other indicted war criminals are to play no role in the
political life of Bosnia-Herzegovina or the Republic of Srpska,"
McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said that Clinton made no decisions at
the meeting, saying "It was a review of decisions that he already
has taken."
</P>
<P>
McCurry warned that Karadzic should be "concerned that the
international community is growing increasingly impatient with the
inability of the war crimes tribunal to try the case that he as
been indicted for."
</P>
<P>
Recent reports have said that the United States is mapping out
a plan to arrest Karadzic, who has a group of guards at his
headquarters in Pale near Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic is believed by the West to be the top war criminal in
Bosnia and the major obstacle on the road to peace there. 
</P>
