<HEADLINE> Animal Husbandry Booms in Henan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Jijiashan, a leading breeding
township in central China's Henan Province, reported a 3,600 ton
egg output in 1996, a level surpassing the grain output by 890
tons. The per capita income earned from eggs accounted for two
thirds of the total income of local residents.
</P>
<P>
Henan has adopted a series of measures in recent years to boost
the development of animal husbandry as a major part of the
agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
Henan's 1996 meat output hit 4.1 million tons, up 23 percent on
the previous year, with the egg output rising by 21.4 percent to
1.7 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, the province has attached special emphasis on using
its rich wheat stock resource to breed herbivores. The current
ratio of pork dropped 80 percent to 62 percent of total meat
output.
</P>
<P>
The province supports development of large-scale breeding
farms, and is currently home to 8,000 large chicken farms and 300
pig farms with more than 1000 pigs each.
</P>
<P>
The development of animal husbandry has also accelerated the
production of other industries such as fodder and livestock
processing and veterinary medicine.
</P>
<P>
The province has over 400 feed factories with a combined annual
output value of two billion yuan, and some 140-odd veterinary
medicine plants, up 71.4 percent on 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
