<DOCNO> XIE19970816.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Falls Again, Share Prices Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- the Indonesian rupiah plunged
again Friday to a new record low against the U.S. dollar and
Jakarta share prices followed suit, falling by almost four
percent, analysts here said today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange dealers said spot rupiah stabilized in Friday
afternoon trading at 2,900 against the greenback.
</P>
<P>
They said the market lost direction following the floating of
the rupiah Thursday. The trading spread widened from five points
before the float to 40 points Friday, exacerbating the fall.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah slumped to 2,960 in midday trading, from an opening
of 2,770/2910 and stabilized in afternoon trading to close at
2,880/2,910.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Mar'ie Mohammad announced on Thursday that
Indonesia abandoned its policy of protecting the currency within
a set trading band which the central bank could intervene to
defend the rupiah from attacks.
</P>
<P>
The float means that the rupiah appreciation against the U.S.
dollar will depend on market mechanism and it will have an impact,
directly or indirectly, on the real sector and business circle.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the fall in the rupiah dragged share prices on the
Jakarta Stock Exchange, with composite index tumbling by 25.30
points or nearly 4 percent to close at 617.70.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover was 386.77 million shares on the regular market,
worth 185.44 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Most stock brokers said Friday's steep intraday fall was
triggered by panic selling by investors as a result of the rupiah
plunge.
</P>
<P>
State minister of National Development Planning Ginandjar
Karatasasmita assured the market Friday that Indonesia's economy
could withstand the float of the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
"We just follow market economic principles. Our economy is
strong enough to face that (the floating of the rupiah)," the
minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
