<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 12 in Ship Wreck in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from a ship wreck
in the central Philippines has risen to 12 as rescuers continued
to search survivors at the rough Biliran Strait where the ship
sank early Friday morning, a Coast Guard officer said today.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Crisolito Augustin, head of the Operation Division of the
Second Coast Guard District based in central Cebu city, told
Xinhua by telephone that so far 12 bodies, all passengers, have
been recovered after a day-and-night rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a report sent to him from the Coast Guard in Biliran
Province this morning, Augustin said 103 people, including 27 crew
members, have been rescued and 16 others are still listed as
missing.
</P>
<P>
Among the 12 fatalities, there were 10 women, one child and one
man, Augustin said, adding that the death toll was feared to go up
due to the bad weather condition on the sea.
</P>
<P>
"The weather forecast said the weather there today is bad, such
as strong winds and big waves," he said.
</P>
<P>
Three naval patrol boats, three helicopters and some civilian
volunteers' vessels were involved in the operation to rake the sea
for survivors Friday. Augustin said the rescue operation is still
on-going.
</P>
<P>
The Coast Guard participating in the rescue operation has
established the exact number of passengers and crew members on
board the 485.5-ton ferry. Augustin said that according to
survivors, the ship carried 88 passengers and 43 crew members.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said 52 passengers and 35 crew members were on
board the ship, which capsized and sank at 2 a.m. near Maripipi
Islet, Biliran Province, after being battered by strong winds and
big waves.
</P>
<P>
The 40-year-old ferry, which has a legal capacity of 449
passengers, was traveling from Cebu city to Tacloban city.
</P>
</TEXT>
