<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Improves Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Efforts by south China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region to develop education in recent years have
paid off, as the area now has a primary school enrollment rate of
98.6 percent for the school age children.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi spent 17.9 billion yuan (2.2 billion US dollars) on its
education program from 1990 to 1995, with an annual increase of
25.5 percent. The government also worked out policies to raise the
salary of teachers and improve their living conditions.
</P>
<P>
The literacy rate has risen to 95 percent among young and
middle-aged people.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of students from minority ethnic groups in
school is higher than the proportion of minority people in the
total population of the region, due to the preferential education
policies for the minority groups.
</P>
<P>
And more people in the region are going to college; over 23
colleges and universities enrolled a total of 63,500 people, a 68
percent rise from 1990. Some 23 colleges specifically for adult
students took in 55,300, up 82 percent from the figure of 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
