<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Confident in Newly-Launched Weather Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- An official said he is confident
in the country's newly-launched Fengyun-2, a geostationary
meteorological satellite, which will begin normal operation later
this year.
</P>
<P>
Today's "China Daily" quoted Wen Kegang, from the China
Meteorological Administration, as saying yesterday that the testing
of the satellite has been good so far since it was sent into orbit
on June 10.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was confident that the new satellite will play
an increasingly important role in accelerating the modernization
of China's meteorological research and furthering the accuracy of
conventional weather forecasting.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that a ground station has successfully received
the satellite's transmitted pictures.
</P>
<P>
Using the satellite, the first of its kind in China, the
country will be able to map clouds covering one-third of the
globe, from Japan to East Africa, according to the paper.  
