<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Unifies Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua)-- China has decided to establish a
unified nationwide basic pension insurance system to replace the
current flexible pilot programmes by the end of 1998, today's
"China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Li Boyong, Minister of Labour, as saying at a
national working meeting on social insurance yesterday that the
ministry has won the approval of the State Council to unify the
pension insurance system and to collect pension insurance funds in
the rest of the provinces.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the transition to the unified system
should be accomplished by the end of the next year in principle,
but certain areas may be given an extension of one year with the
State Council's consent.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Li asked local governments and labour
departments to promote combining unemployment insurance with the
"re-employment project" and to establish medical care, child birth
and industrial injury insurance.
</P>
<P>
Li emphasised the importance of properly managing the pension
insurance fund, "which must not be used for any form of investment
except the purchase of State treasury bonds."
</P>
<P>
Official statistics indicate that about 88 million Chinese
people, 23 million of whom are retirees, have joined the pension
insurance scheme.
</P>
<P>
However, one-fifth of the country's urban employees remain
outside it. Most of them are workers in overseas-funded or private
enterprises, self-employed business people or rural labourers
working in cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
