<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine's An-70 to Premiere in MAX-97 Air Show in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's newest An-70 plane will
attend the MAX-97 International Air Show in Moscow, press reported
here today.
</P>
<P>
The military STOL transport plane, made by the Antonov Design
and Production Complex in Kiev and regarded as one of the most
advanced aircraft in the world, will be on show from August 19 to
24.
</P>
<P>
Capable of using ground airstrips with a runway as short as 600
meters, AN-70 can lift payloads up to 47 tons. With a payload of
20 tons, the plane will fly a distance of more than 7,500
kilometers at an average cruising speed between 750 and 800
kilometer per hour.
</P>
<P>
The air show in Zhukovshk, a suburban town of Moscow, ranks the
world's fifth largest and most prestigious following similar
events in France's La Bourge, Farnboro, Singapore and Dubai.
</P>
<P>
The Antonov Design and Production Complex disclosed that
several companies in Germany, Britain, France and some other
countries have expressed interest in the Ukrainian aircraft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970816.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Stopping Rising Construction Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 16 (Xinhua) -- To control the cost of housing
China's capital has stopped or reduced 36 types of construction
fees.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, excessive construction costs have resulted in
rapidly-rising housing costs and have hindered the healthy growth
of the city's real estate business.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, the city has removed 25 construction
fees charged for wire checking, auditing construction costs, and
commissions charged for increasing power supplies, and has reduced
the amount charged in 11 other fees.
</P>
<P>
Official with the commodity pricing department say they will
increase controls on construction costs, and that people who do
not comply with the new regulations will receive administrative
penalties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970816.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Costa Rican government financial deficit
reached 224.4 million U.S. dollars during the first seven months
of 1997, a 9 percent reduction over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government got revenue for 842.4 million dollars in July,
a 19 percent increase over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
It allocated 1.0668 billion dollars for salaries, pensions,
funds for education, and others, a 12 percent increase over the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua registered in July its second highest
monthly inflation of 1997, when this index reached 1.51 percent.
The increase of consumer prices in June was 1.97 percent,
the highest so far this year, said the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The country registered a 4.66 percent inflation in the first
seven months of 1997, a figure lower than the 5.67 percent
accumulated during the same period of 1996. Inflation reckoned
during the last 12 months until July was 11.03 percent, against
11.08 registered from August of 1995 to July of 1996.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico was ranked seventh in the preferences of
world tourists and first in Latin America in 1996, according to a
report from the International Tourism Alliance.
</P>
<P>
Based on preliminary figures, the document explains tht Mexico
received 21,000,732 foreign tourists last year, 7.8 percent more
than in 1995. Foreign visitors spent 6.898 billion dollars in
1996, 11.9 percent more than in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan milk production could reach this year a
record 1.04 billion liters, 4 percent more than the 1996 yield, as
reported by Ramon Fernandez, president of the National Association
of Milk Producers of Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Fernandez made this prodiction when he commented a series of
agreements signed by the association with the Defense Ministry for
the implementation of several works aimed at providing water to
3,000 milk producers in sufficient quantity and quality.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The rate of poor persons in the Argentine
capital and its suburbs dropped from 27.9 percent to 26.3 percent
between October of 1996 and May of this year, according to the
National Statistics and Census Institute (INDEC).
</P>
<P>
According to INDEC, despite the improvement, more than 3
million people and 650,000 households in the capital and the
environments of Buenos Aires still live in a situation of
indigence and with unsatisfied basic needs.
</P>
<P>
More than a third of the total population of the country
concentrates in Buenos Aires and its peripheral areas, and poverty
in those areas reached its highest levels during the 1989-1990
period, when it affected 40 percent of the population.
</P>
</TEXT>
