<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panamanian economy registered a 3.7 increase
compared to the first quarter of 1996, announced President Ernesto
Perez Balladares.
</P>
<P>
The increase is attributed to the privatization of some state
enterprises, the restructuring of the public debt and an
aggressive investment in infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.775 billion dollars have been invested in the last two
years, mainly in the social sector and in infrastructure, while
the debt of the country has diminished by more than 446 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombian exports to the Andean Community
during the first five months of this year contracted 0.2 percent
decrease against the same period of 1996, when they ended at 799
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The drop was caused by the descent in sales to Peru and
Venezuela, which diminished 14.7 percent and 3.3 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Colombian exports to Venezuela, its main trade partner, during
the mentioned period, were worth 347.8 million dollars. Sales to
Ecuador and Bolivia were 198.8 million and 15.3 million,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Foreign direct investments in Venezuela during the
first seven months of this year were more than 184.18 million
dollars, an increase of more than 25.572 million dollars compared
to the same period of 1996, when they reached 158.607 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Investment Superintendency announced that the
sectors that attracted more foreign capitals were manufacturing
industry with more than 87 million dollars, and other financial
and real estate services, with more than 44 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is also included with more than 24 million dollars,
and construction with more than 22 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile exported more than 404 million dollars worth
of salmon during the first semester of this year, a 30.5 percent
increase over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Salmon and Trout Producers announced that
95.2 million kilos of salmon, worth 264 million dollars, were sent
abroad during the first six months of this year, and of this
amount 64 million kilos went to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Chile exported to the United States 23 million kilos worth 99
million dollars, and Brazil imported 12.2 million dollars of the
product.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian gold reserves increased 112 percent in
1996 over those of 1995, going from 800 tons to 1,700 tons,
said the Mines and Energy Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Brazil exported gold last year for 583 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
