<HEADLINE> Rapeseed Research By Chinese And European Agronomists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese agronomists and their
European counterparts will co-operate in improving rapeseed plants
by using gene technology.
</P>
<P>
The research is the second co-operative endeavor, following a
wheat breeding study using gene engineering, according to
researchers at the Zhejiang Agricultural Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and European gene engineers are studying the quality of
rapeseed, disease resistance, and the use of hybrids. German
geneticist Heiko Becker will act as co-ordinator for the research
program.
</P>
<P>
Scientists will also compare genetic differences between
Chinese breeds and European types of rapeseed, a plant of European
origin grown as food for sheep and pigs and for the oil produced
from its seeds.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Agricultural Research Institute, Central China
Agricultural University, a Sweden research center, and a British
agricultural research institute expressed an interest in the
four-year program, which is expected to cost 750,000 Ecu (about
798,000 US dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
