<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Finishes 1-2 in European 1m Springboard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Vera Iliyna paced her
teammate Irina Lashko for a 1-2 finish in the one-meter
springboard finals at the European Swimming Championships in
Seville on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Iliyna, the 23-year-old defending champion in both springboard
events, edged Lashko and Dorte Lindner of Germany to second and
third.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow native, a diminutive 1.60 meters, was second prior
to her final dive, a difficult reverse one-and-a-half somersault
with a one-and-a-half twist.
</P>
<P>
However, Iliyna who finished seventh in Atlanta, finished with
268.14 points to 264.72 for Lashko and 264.36 for Lindner.
</P>
<P>
Hungary picked up the gold in the women's 25-kilometer swim as
Rita Kovacs won in 5 hours 21 minutes 58 seconds, beating Italian
Valeria Casprini to second in 5:23:28 and Edith van Dijk of the
Netherlands third in 5:25:28.
</P>
<P>
The victory adds to the 27-year-old Hungarian' long-distance
laurels. Started her long-distance swimming six years ago, Kovacs
was second at 25 kilometers in the 1994 world championships and
won the five kilometers in the 1995 European championships.
</P>
<P>
Casprini, the 21-year-old Italian from Florence, led the first
23 kilometers until she was overtaken by Kovacs.
</P>
<P>
In the women's synchronized solo, Olga Sedakova of Russia took
the gold with 99.240 points, chased by Virginie Dedieu of France
on 97.440 and Giovanna Gurlando of Italy on 95.960. 
</P>
</TEXT>
