<HEADLINE> 1.2 Million Pounds of Beef Recalled in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government today
recalled 1.2 million pounds of ground beef produced by an Arkansas
company because of new evidence of possible contamination by E.
coli bacteria.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman urged those who has
purchased frozen ground-beef patties since June 4 to check their
freezers to determine if any of the Hudson Foods Co. products are
there. If so, they should be returned to the point of purchase.
</P>
<P>
The suspect ground beef was produced at Hudson's Nebraska plant
in Columbus, Nebraska on June 4, June 5 and June 9. Government
officials are trying to determine if other contaminated products
were produced there.
</P>
<P>
"USDA is conducting a thorough investigation at the plant to
ensure that no unsafe product is being allowed to go into
commerce," Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
Although Hudson voluntarily recalled some 40,000 pounds of
hamburger earlier this week after health officials in Colorado
traced the illnesses of about 20 people to hamburger patties they
ate in early June.
</P>
<P>
E. coli bacteria can cause severe diarrhea, cramps and
dehydration and can be fatal. The young, elderly and people with
weak immune systems are most susceptible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
