<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Disappointment toward Israel's Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The State Department on
Friday denied allegations in the Israeli press that the United
States was disappointed with the extent to which Israel had eased
sanctions against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli newspaper Haaretz claimed earlier today that
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu betrayed promises he had
made to U.S. mediator Dennis Ross regarding the extent to which
sanctions were to be lifted.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions, including the closure of Israeli-Palestinian
borders and withholding of tax revenues, were imposed in the
aftermath of a suicide bombing on July 30, which killed 16 people
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"It is understandable that they would undergo a certain degree
of intensified security measures in order to try to deter and
prevent any new terrorist acts of the kind that so traumatized the
nation a couple of weeks ago," State Department spokesman James
Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But he also said: "We believe that the decision to withhold
funds from the Palestinian Authority and some of the closure with
respect to humanitarian goods and movement of peoples were
counter-productive and unwise." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
