<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Unveils Celebrations for New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- As the year 2000 is drawing
near, U.S. President Bill Clinton Friday announced a series of
events to usher in a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
In the hallowed halls of the U.S. Archives building, Clinton
outlined a multi-year list of goals, projects and celebrations,
and urged Americans to use the White House site on the Internet to
suggest even more.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "With the millennium, we must now decide how to
think about our commitment to the future."
</P>
<P>
However, much of his list consisted of previously announced
activities, and White House officials acknowledged they had not
developed any single blockbuster idea.
</P>
<P>
Ellen McCulloch-Lovell, director of the White House Millennium
Program, said, "We're looking for ideas," adding "I think that
people understand that this is a milestone in human history. And
if there were a big thing that would mark it, we'd certainly be
receptive to that."
</P>
<P>
The events announced by Clinton include:
</P>
<P>
-- a White House lecture series;
</P>
<P>
-- the president's longstanding campaign goal of connecting
schools to the Internet;
</P>
<P>
-- a series of television advertisements known as "Millennium
Minutes;" and
</P>
<P>
-- the dispatching of teams of photographers nationwide "to
capture their visions of America at the turn of the 21st century."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
