<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Forces Begins Build-up in Bosnia for Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
started to rotate its troops deployed in Bosnia, increasing the
number to between 11,000 and 12,000 during the forthcoming
elections, Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Army spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Steve Campbell said an
advance party from the Second Armoured Cavalry Regiment, now in
Tazar, Hungary went to Tuzla in Bosnia to prepare for the arrival
of troops starting next week.
</P>
<P>
The troops they will replace, from 3rd Brigade of the 1st
Infantry Division, will not leave Bosnia until about two weeks
after the Bosnian elections in September.
</P>
<P>
"It's an increase, it's a planned increase, and it's done for a
reason," Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon told reporters on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The in-and-out move, which will take place over a series of
weeks, allows for an overlap to occur just as Bosnia plans its
mid-September municipal elections, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
"We did this before with the national elections (in Bosnia)...
It's temporary. We've been clear and public about this for
months," he said.
</P>
<P>
There are currently about 8,000 U.S. troops in Bosnia, a part
of more than 30,000 multinational forces which help enforce the
Bosnia peace accords signed in Dayton, the U.S., in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The troops are due to leave Bosnia by the deadline of June
next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
